1
00:00:04,365 --> 00:00:08,389
Hi everyone, let's get started.

2
00:00:08,389 --> 00:00:10,150
There might be a few more people coming in,

3
00:00:10,150 --> 00:00:12,992
but we'll let them feel like they're late

4
00:00:12,992 --> 00:00:14,434
and they're missing out, that's more fun.

5
00:00:14,434 --> 00:00:17,556
Before we get going, can you put your mobile phones

6
00:00:17,556 --> 00:00:20,579
on silent and at the end, can you please remember

7
00:00:20,579 --> 00:00:22,220
to fill in your session evaluation form

8
00:00:22,220 --> 00:00:24,342
because it's always nice to hear what people think

9
00:00:24,342 --> 00:00:25,843
and that would make me feel very happy.

10
00:00:25,843 --> 00:00:26,864
So thank you very much for coming.

11
00:00:28,064 --> 00:00:34,656
Right, my name is John Ingold and I'm the narrative director of Inkle. We're a small

12
00:00:34,656 --> 00:00:38,303
independent studio from the UK and we made these things

13
00:00:39,007 --> 00:00:44,468
So we made 80 Days and Sorcery, which are games, and we also made Ink, which is not a game.

14
00:00:44,468 --> 00:00:47,749
It's a scripting language for interactive fiction.

15
00:00:47,749 --> 00:00:52,790
But it kind of demonstrates our philosophy in the way that it's built and the way that it's designed.

16
00:00:52,790 --> 00:00:56,872
It's sort of human-focused, it's quite wibbly-wobbly, it likes to branch a lot,

17
00:00:56,872 --> 00:00:59,292
it doesn't have an intrinsic structure, it's much more ad hoc.

18
00:00:59,292 --> 00:01:00,933
And those are all things that we like to do.

19
00:01:01,972 --> 00:01:05,862
They're all quite strange things to want to do within a programming context,

20
00:01:05,862 --> 00:01:08,529
and they come from the same root philosophy.

21
00:01:08,529 --> 00:01:10,334
All of these things have the same root philosophy.

22
00:01:11,005 --> 00:01:13,086
Today, I'm going to talk about our new title.

23
00:01:13,086 --> 00:01:15,848
I'm going to talk about our new system that we've been doing.

24
00:01:15,848 --> 00:01:18,550
We've overhauled things quite a lot to produce some, I think,

25
00:01:18,550 --> 00:01:20,651
really quite extraordinary results.

26
00:01:20,651 --> 00:01:23,613
And I hope that I will convince you of that.

27
00:01:23,613 --> 00:01:25,094
But it's a good idea to just back up a bit

28
00:01:25,094 --> 00:01:28,616
and see how we get there, so you can see the process that we've

29
00:01:28,616 --> 00:01:29,557
been through.

30
00:01:29,557 --> 00:01:32,239
Apologies to anyone who's come to any of my previous GDC talks,

31
00:01:32,239 --> 00:01:34,400
because a little bit of this will be recapped,

32
00:01:34,400 --> 00:01:36,081
but I'll try to get through it smoothly.

33
00:01:37,224 --> 00:01:44,267
I said who we are and I said who I am, but I want to say what we do in a philosophical sentence.

34
00:01:44,267 --> 00:01:47,108
So the best I could come up with was this.

35
00:01:47,108 --> 00:01:50,669
We make playable stories with high player freedom.

36
00:01:50,669 --> 00:01:52,770
This is a really carefully chosen rubric.

37
00:01:52,770 --> 00:01:54,091
I worried about this a lot.

38
00:01:54,091 --> 00:01:56,632
I didn't ask anyone else on my team if they thought it was appropriate

39
00:01:56,632 --> 00:01:58,212
because I didn't want them to tell me that it wasn't.

40
00:02:00,073 --> 00:02:02,475
and it's obviously composed of two main bits.

41
00:02:02,475 --> 00:02:05,217
You'll notice first up that it doesn't have the word game

42
00:02:05,217 --> 00:02:07,579
in it anywhere, because game's a useless word that

43
00:02:07,579 --> 00:02:09,400
doesn't mean anything.

44
00:02:09,400 --> 00:02:12,002
And it does say playable stories,

45
00:02:12,002 --> 00:02:14,044
and I feel like that's quite honest.

46
00:02:14,044 --> 00:02:16,826
When we design one of our games, products,

47
00:02:16,826 --> 00:02:19,028
when we design one of our products,

48
00:02:19,028 --> 00:02:21,169
we start with the story, we start with the character,

49
00:02:21,169 --> 00:02:22,911
what we want the player to do and feel,

50
00:02:22,911 --> 00:02:25,673
and then we try to design the minimum number.

51
00:02:26,273 --> 00:02:29,854
of mechanics possible to generate that sensation.

52
00:02:29,854 --> 00:02:31,834
So, sorcery is a fantasy adventure.

53
00:02:31,834 --> 00:02:33,334
You have a sword, you have a spell book,

54
00:02:33,334 --> 00:02:35,235
you go around clobbering monsters,

55
00:02:35,235 --> 00:02:35,855
there are some potions.

56
00:02:35,855 --> 00:02:38,876
We try to keep it as light touch as possible.

57
00:02:38,876 --> 00:02:41,496
There isn't any crafting because no one actually does that

58
00:02:41,496 --> 00:02:42,637
when they're on a fantasy adventure.

59
00:02:42,637 --> 00:02:45,417
It would be ridiculous until Breath of Wild came along

60
00:02:45,417 --> 00:02:47,578
and did that rather well, actually.

61
00:02:47,578 --> 00:02:49,718
Similarly, In 80 Days is a playable story.

62
00:02:49,718 --> 00:02:50,638
It's about traveling.

63
00:02:50,638 --> 00:02:52,379
So you travel, you pack your suitcases,

64
00:02:52,379 --> 00:02:53,859
you talk to people, that's basically it.

65
00:02:54,850 --> 00:02:57,892
The second thing is high player freedom.

66
00:02:57,892 --> 00:03:01,974
And again, that's a slightly surprising phrase to use.

67
00:03:01,974 --> 00:03:04,495
I haven't said high player agency,

68
00:03:04,495 --> 00:03:05,936
and that's quite deliberate.

69
00:03:05,936 --> 00:03:09,718
To me, agency suggests that players can strategize

70
00:03:09,718 --> 00:03:11,639
to achieve a particular outcome.

71
00:03:11,639 --> 00:03:13,960
And in our games, that's very rarely true.

72
00:03:13,960 --> 00:03:16,462
We work within highly contextual environments

73
00:03:16,462 --> 00:03:18,243
where what happens one moment

74
00:03:18,243 --> 00:03:20,224
might not be available in the next moment.

75
00:03:20,224 --> 00:03:22,005
So strategy can be quite difficult.

76
00:03:22,005 --> 00:03:24,346
What I'm saying is our games are inherently very unfair.

77
00:03:24,706 --> 00:03:25,586
and I'm good with that.

78
00:03:25,586 --> 00:03:29,827
But what we do try to offer is we try to offer a sense of freedom,

79
00:03:29,827 --> 00:03:31,828
that in any given moment in this story,

80
00:03:31,828 --> 00:03:35,149
you can behave in the sort of way you might want to behave,

81
00:03:35,149 --> 00:03:37,809
given the limitations of the interface or whatever.

82
00:03:37,809 --> 00:03:39,710
So you shouldn't feel that you're stuck on a track,

83
00:03:39,710 --> 00:03:42,270
you shouldn't feel that you're pressing the only button

84
00:03:42,270 --> 00:03:43,831
that the author gave you to press,

85
00:03:43,831 --> 00:03:46,011
you shouldn't feel that you're just tapping through options.

86
00:03:46,011 --> 00:03:47,892
That's high player freedom,

87
00:03:47,892 --> 00:03:50,012
but I wouldn't go so far as to say that it was agency.

88
00:03:51,235 --> 00:03:58,339
Nonetheless, even though we don't necessarily allow the player to strategize and achieve a particular outcome,

89
00:03:58,339 --> 00:04:03,001
we still have a problem to solve here because we have an oxymoron between those two things.

90
00:04:03,001 --> 00:04:08,024
A story is inherently unfree and freedom is inherently pretty dull for storytelling,

91
00:04:08,024 --> 00:04:11,966
actually. If people can do anything, they tend to just muck about. So how do we deal with that?

92
00:04:11,966 --> 00:04:17,309
Well, okay, we have two simplifications. The first one, we tend to use an episodic structure.

93
00:04:18,049 --> 00:04:22,314
So almost all of our games are structured like 1980s Star Trek series is.

94
00:04:22,314 --> 00:04:26,079
You go to somewhere, you do something, any amount of complicated stuff can happen,

95
00:04:26,079 --> 00:04:29,643
but by the end of the episode you can be pretty confident that Picard's wife is

96
00:04:29,643 --> 00:04:32,707
going to turn out to be a hologram of a thousand-year-old dead woman,

97
00:04:32,707 --> 00:04:36,651
or an evil robot, or some other kind of mental illness that he's got from a

98
00:04:36,651 --> 00:04:37,232
clonk on the head.

99
00:04:37,889 --> 00:04:41,013
By the end of the episode, very little is carried into the next episode,

100
00:04:41,013 --> 00:04:43,836
because that's the most convenient way to write it.

101
00:04:43,836 --> 00:04:45,899
And that's what we do in sorcery, and that's what we do in 80 Days.

102
00:04:45,899 --> 00:04:48,602
We used to say, what happens in Vegas stays in Vegas,

103
00:04:48,602 --> 00:04:51,265
and that's basically true of the construction of 80 Days.

104
00:04:51,912 --> 00:04:53,794
There's nothing wrong with that, that's fine.

105
00:04:53,794 --> 00:04:56,257
Assassin's Creed does exactly the same thing.

106
00:04:56,257 --> 00:04:58,999
It will say you can take out this fortress via stealth

107
00:04:58,999 --> 00:05:00,881
or via brute force, it's always brute force

108
00:05:00,881 --> 00:05:02,603
because their stealth is so terribly balanced

109
00:05:02,603 --> 00:05:04,024
that it doesn't work at all.

110
00:05:04,024 --> 00:05:05,506
But by the end of that encounter,

111
00:05:05,506 --> 00:05:06,587
when you go to the next one,

112
00:05:06,587 --> 00:05:09,009
it doesn't matter what you did in the last one.

113
00:05:09,009 --> 00:05:09,750
Episodic structure.

114
00:05:10,694 --> 00:05:15,376
The other thing that we do is the thing I suppose in a way we're most famous for, perhaps,

115
00:05:15,376 --> 00:05:19,398
is we use a content-heavy approach to branching.

116
00:05:19,398 --> 00:05:20,879
We use a scale-first approach.

117
00:05:20,879 --> 00:05:24,721
So when we do branch, because of course we do branch, we do give you some agency and

118
00:05:24,721 --> 00:05:28,783
some influence over the outcome of your adventures, we just write more.

119
00:05:28,783 --> 00:05:29,723
We just make more.

120
00:05:29,723 --> 00:05:33,965
And we can do that because we're delivering everything through text, historically, and

121
00:05:33,965 --> 00:05:37,267
it's very easy, well, it's relatively easy to produce lots of text.

122
00:05:38,205 --> 00:05:40,487
So all of that is where we are and what we've done,

123
00:05:40,487 --> 00:05:43,149
which brings me to our next project, our new project,

124
00:05:43,149 --> 00:05:43,950
which is this thing.

125
00:05:43,950 --> 00:05:45,992
It's called Heaven's Vault.

126
00:05:45,992 --> 00:05:48,293
It's a archeological narrative adventure.

127
00:05:48,293 --> 00:05:50,215
You play as this lady, Aliyah al-Azra,

128
00:05:50,215 --> 00:05:51,736
who sails an open-world nebula

129
00:05:51,736 --> 00:05:54,999
and discovers lost ruin sites and ancient inscriptions

130
00:05:54,999 --> 00:05:56,720
in an entire ancient language,

131
00:05:56,720 --> 00:05:58,902
which we've invented for the game,

132
00:05:58,902 --> 00:06:00,803
which is absolutely not what this talk is about.

133
00:06:02,071 --> 00:06:04,112
And from a narrative design point of view,

134
00:06:04,112 --> 00:06:08,273
Heaven's Vault had two core elements that we started with.

135
00:06:08,273 --> 00:06:10,614
This isn't even retrofitted, this is actually true.

136
00:06:10,614 --> 00:06:11,554
Joe and I sat down and said,

137
00:06:11,554 --> 00:06:13,534
what do we want to achieve with this project

138
00:06:13,534 --> 00:06:15,875
since we've done what we wanted to achieve

139
00:06:15,875 --> 00:06:18,316
with linear prose fiction?

140
00:06:18,316 --> 00:06:19,916
And the two things were, firstly,

141
00:06:20,697 --> 00:06:24,497
To take the episodic structure and turn it into a single continuous plot.

142
00:06:24,497 --> 00:06:25,598
Fine, okay?

143
00:06:25,598 --> 00:06:29,339
We wanted everything that the player does to further some core narrative.

144
00:06:29,339 --> 00:06:31,579
That doesn't mean we're not using episodes.

145
00:06:31,579 --> 00:06:34,800
I'll talk about our exact structure later in the talk.

146
00:06:34,800 --> 00:06:39,821
But the idea is instead every episode should further the core narrative of the game

147
00:06:39,821 --> 00:06:41,681
in some meaningful, consistent and solid way.

148
00:06:42,162 --> 00:06:45,363
We're trying to not have too much in the way of standalone encounters,

149
00:06:45,363 --> 00:06:47,924
but rather encounters that make sense within the narrative.

150
00:06:47,924 --> 00:06:51,745
If you like, it's Star Trek Discovery rather than Star Trek The Next Generation,

151
00:06:51,745 --> 00:06:53,486
only without the torture porn Klingon sex.

152
00:06:53,486 --> 00:07:00,769
The second thing that we do is we wanted to move away from purely text-based delivery

153
00:07:00,769 --> 00:07:02,129
to a 3D game world to explore.

154
00:07:02,129 --> 00:07:05,351
Quite why we wanted to do that, I look back on and I'm not really sure.

155
00:07:05,351 --> 00:07:07,251
It's a terrible financial decision.

156
00:07:07,251 --> 00:07:07,491
It's been a...

157
00:07:08,655 --> 00:07:10,518
extended the length of the project hugely,

158
00:07:10,518 --> 00:07:12,620
hopefully people will think it is pretty,

159
00:07:12,620 --> 00:07:14,783
which is quite a good reason to do something.

160
00:07:14,783 --> 00:07:17,466
It does mean, though, we have necessarily

161
00:07:17,466 --> 00:07:18,748
a limited number of locations,

162
00:07:18,748 --> 00:07:20,590
we have a limited size of cast,

163
00:07:20,590 --> 00:07:22,893
so we can't use a scale-first approach

164
00:07:22,893 --> 00:07:25,616
to simply make that problem of branching content go away.

165
00:07:25,616 --> 00:07:26,657
We have to reuse stuff,

166
00:07:26,657 --> 00:07:28,339
we have to be a bit different in our redundancy.

167
00:07:29,118 --> 00:07:32,320
So one thing I like about this game is I like the title.

168
00:07:32,320 --> 00:07:33,041
I like the title a lot.

169
00:07:33,041 --> 00:07:34,562
It took us a long time to come up with the title.

170
00:07:34,562 --> 00:07:37,083
And one of the reasons I like it is we had our two crutches.

171
00:07:37,083 --> 00:07:39,665
We have thrown them both away simultaneously

172
00:07:39,665 --> 00:07:42,907
in a leap of faith, a heaven's vault, if you will,

173
00:07:42,907 --> 00:07:45,508
to create this new game.

174
00:07:45,508 --> 00:07:47,169
And in order to do that, we've had to expand

175
00:07:47,169 --> 00:07:50,471
our sort of core philosophy a little bit as well

176
00:07:50,471 --> 00:07:53,393
to produce what I think is the best description of it

177
00:07:53,393 --> 00:07:55,134
I have so far, which is this.

178
00:07:55,134 --> 00:07:57,215
We are now a company making a narrative adventure

179
00:07:57,215 --> 00:07:57,896
game type thing.

180
00:07:59,130 --> 00:08:00,910
with high player freedom.

181
00:08:00,910 --> 00:08:01,690
So that's the goal.

182
00:08:01,690 --> 00:08:03,531
That's what I'm attempting to present to you

183
00:08:03,531 --> 00:08:06,391
is our system for producing a narrative adventure game

184
00:08:06,391 --> 00:08:07,852
type thing with high player freedom.

185
00:08:07,852 --> 00:08:10,352
Now, if you were to walk into a design meeting

186
00:08:10,352 --> 00:08:12,193
with that rubric, of course,

187
00:08:12,193 --> 00:08:14,653
everyone would say that I can see an immediate question,

188
00:08:14,653 --> 00:08:16,814
which is you're what?

189
00:08:16,814 --> 00:08:19,394
After all, what is freedom exactly?

190
00:08:19,394 --> 00:08:20,354
What does it mean?

191
00:08:20,354 --> 00:08:22,435
How do we offer it to a player?

192
00:08:22,435 --> 00:08:23,735
What are we actually talking about?

193
00:08:24,496 --> 00:08:25,457
This is really interesting.

194
00:08:25,457 --> 00:08:26,738
This is a really interesting question.

195
00:08:26,738 --> 00:08:28,199
What do we mean when we say player freedom?

196
00:08:28,199 --> 00:08:31,041
When we say player agency, we're pretty good at

197
00:08:31,041 --> 00:08:31,721
analyzing that.

198
00:08:31,721 --> 00:08:34,443
We can say, well, can you formulate a strategy?

199
00:08:34,443 --> 00:08:35,264
Can you execute a plan?

200
00:08:35,264 --> 00:08:36,504
Those are the sort of questions.

201
00:08:36,504 --> 00:08:40,067
But what's the right question for this freedom concept that

202
00:08:40,067 --> 00:08:42,729
I'm sort of loosely defining?

203
00:08:42,729 --> 00:08:45,531
Well, I think the right question to be asking is

204
00:08:45,531 --> 00:08:45,851
actually.

205
00:08:46,632 --> 00:08:49,455
What question is the player asking themselves?

206
00:08:49,455 --> 00:08:51,557
That's the question we should be asking.

207
00:08:51,557 --> 00:08:53,139
What's the player thinking?

208
00:08:53,139 --> 00:08:54,360
So here is my freedom axis.

209
00:08:54,360 --> 00:08:57,604
There's my beautiful graph of a freedom axis.

210
00:08:57,604 --> 00:08:59,746
And at the very bottom of the freedom axis,

211
00:08:59,746 --> 00:09:02,849
and I want to stress this is not pejorative,

212
00:09:02,849 --> 00:09:05,312
but the least free games, the most tightly linear games,

213
00:09:05,312 --> 00:09:07,835
the player is asking, what am I supposed to do now?

214
00:09:08,546 --> 00:09:10,647
What am I meant to do next?

215
00:09:10,647 --> 00:09:12,787
And we've all played games like that.

216
00:09:12,787 --> 00:09:14,048
Monkey Island is like that.

217
00:09:14,048 --> 00:09:15,248
Uncharted is like that.

218
00:09:15,248 --> 00:09:16,509
Shadow of the Colossus is like that.

219
00:09:16,509 --> 00:09:17,249
Here I am in a situation.

220
00:09:17,249 --> 00:09:18,829
What's the thing I'm supposed to do?

221
00:09:18,829 --> 00:09:22,411
What have I not seen yet that I'm supposed to see?

222
00:09:22,411 --> 00:09:25,892
Now, we have to be a bit honest with ourselves here.

223
00:09:25,892 --> 00:09:28,213
I don't think the designers at Naughty Dog

224
00:09:28,213 --> 00:09:30,773
were really hoping that when you play Uncharted,

225
00:09:30,773 --> 00:09:32,394
you're thinking, what am I meant to do now?

226
00:09:33,695 --> 00:09:35,716
I think that's not what they were going for,

227
00:09:35,716 --> 00:09:38,197
but it is definitely true that we are thinking that,

228
00:09:38,197 --> 00:09:40,798
and a lot of the best level design moments

229
00:09:40,798 --> 00:09:43,640
in Uncharted 4 are jokes specifically about the fact

230
00:09:43,640 --> 00:09:45,701
that they know people are thinking like this.

231
00:09:45,701 --> 00:09:47,922
You walk into a room, you can't see any way forward,

232
00:09:47,922 --> 00:09:49,523
you think, what am I supposed to do now?

233
00:09:49,523 --> 00:09:51,363
You turn around and the exit is behind you.

234
00:09:51,363 --> 00:09:53,625
That's a gag set up by a level designer

235
00:09:53,625 --> 00:09:55,686
because they know that you're thinking this question

236
00:09:55,686 --> 00:09:57,186
because it's a tightly linear game.

237
00:09:57,186 --> 00:09:59,407
So if we open it out a little bit more,

238
00:09:59,407 --> 00:10:01,288
the next question is, what can I do?

239
00:10:02,891 --> 00:10:04,613
and obviously there are games that fit that mold.

240
00:10:04,613 --> 00:10:06,534
In Assassin's Creed, I ask myself, what can I do now?

241
00:10:06,534 --> 00:10:07,735
Well, I could go over here,

242
00:10:07,735 --> 00:10:09,677
I could approach this stealthily and get that wrong,

243
00:10:09,677 --> 00:10:11,999
I could attack this guy, whatever.

244
00:10:11,999 --> 00:10:13,360
The Witcher, RPGs in general.

245
00:10:13,360 --> 00:10:16,663
80 Days in Sorcery, of course, sits at the top of this class,

246
00:10:16,663 --> 00:10:19,946
the very paragon of the example of the broader game,

247
00:10:19,946 --> 00:10:21,468
and I'm sure you'll agree, all of that.

248
00:10:21,468 --> 00:10:21,628
But what's...

249
00:10:24,012 --> 00:10:26,893
Above that, what's even freer than the question,

250
00:10:26,893 --> 00:10:27,313
what can I do?

251
00:10:27,313 --> 00:10:30,274
Well, the one that we're aiming for, the one that we love,

252
00:10:30,274 --> 00:10:32,234
the one that we should be targeting

253
00:10:32,234 --> 00:10:38,155
if we are narrative designers, is, yikes, what have I done?

254
00:10:38,155 --> 00:10:38,996
That's the perfect state.

255
00:10:38,996 --> 00:10:42,816
That's the sweet spot that we actually want to achieve.

256
00:10:42,816 --> 00:10:45,637
It's very rare for a game to achieve this consistently

257
00:10:45,637 --> 00:10:47,357
the whole way through, and that's OK.

258
00:10:47,357 --> 00:10:48,018
It's a target.

259
00:10:49,736 --> 00:10:51,998
But I felt that quite often playing Horizon Zero Dawn.

260
00:10:51,998 --> 00:10:55,081
I would often go to a dinosaur, lay a complex system of traps,

261
00:10:55,081 --> 00:10:57,903
they would all go hideously wrong, the robots would plow straight through them,

262
00:10:57,903 --> 00:11:01,146
and I'd be attacked by some great big thing I wasn't qualified to deal with,

263
00:11:01,146 --> 00:11:02,427
and I would think, yikes, what have I done?

264
00:11:02,427 --> 00:11:05,730
And that was great. That was a genuine sense that I had freedom,

265
00:11:05,730 --> 00:11:07,692
and with freedom comes great, uh...

266
00:11:09,393 --> 00:11:11,794
Responsibility? Great. Ability to mess things up, right?

267
00:11:11,794 --> 00:11:14,095
When we're free to do things, we're free to get stuff wrong.

268
00:11:14,095 --> 00:11:18,156
Obviously, dishonor plays with this, and thief is kind of the ur-example.

269
00:11:18,156 --> 00:11:21,698
A level of thief always starts off with taking one minor decision

270
00:11:21,698 --> 00:11:25,459
that escalates into a farce of hiding guards in cupboards and running away.

271
00:11:25,459 --> 00:11:27,240
It's never been bettered, I think.

272
00:11:28,099 --> 00:11:34,904
A couple of other comments, obviously the ordering of the game in this list could be debated, but why would you bother?

273
00:11:34,904 --> 00:11:38,826
It's not a classification, not all games fit into this in any meaningful way.

274
00:11:38,826 --> 00:11:41,788
If you're playing Minesweeper, you're thinking, why am I playing this?

275
00:11:41,788 --> 00:11:47,632
If you're playing Fortnite, you're thinking, what's going on?

276
00:11:47,632 --> 00:11:51,995
You know, neither of those games are charting here.

277
00:11:53,243 --> 00:11:56,186
But yeah, what I want to think about is,

278
00:11:56,186 --> 00:11:56,787
is yikes, what have I done?

279
00:11:56,787 --> 00:12:01,273
And the examples that I gave were all systemized mechanics.

280
00:12:01,273 --> 00:12:02,695
They were all systems-based games.

281
00:12:02,695 --> 00:12:05,298
But I'm not saying that we need to make a systems-based game.

282
00:12:05,298 --> 00:12:08,562
And I'm not saying that I have any interest in making a systems-based game.

283
00:12:08,562 --> 00:12:09,183
I really don't.

284
00:12:09,183 --> 00:12:11,246
They're quite repetitive and boring, actually.

285
00:12:13,016 --> 00:12:18,801
I'm a firm believer, as I hope I've expressed if you've seen any of my previous talks, that

286
00:12:18,801 --> 00:12:23,706
it's fine to change the player's options in a contextual way all the time.

287
00:12:23,706 --> 00:12:28,470
That's not a problem, so long as the options that you provide make sense.

288
00:12:28,470 --> 00:12:32,554
The reason systematic games are great is the player has real confidence that they know

289
00:12:32,554 --> 00:12:34,816
what they'll be able to do in five minutes' time.

290
00:12:34,816 --> 00:12:35,597
They can plan.

291
00:12:36,317 --> 00:12:41,479
You can't plan if the choices are being changed up underneath you from turn to turn to turn as they

292
00:12:41,479 --> 00:12:46,561
are in A Choose Your Own Adventure, as they are in 80 Days, but if you trust the author to provide

293
00:12:46,561 --> 00:12:52,943
you with the kind of options that you want then that problem goes away largely actually. So our

294
00:12:52,943 --> 00:12:58,585
goal is to create choices with good affordances that people can just about predict and that appear

295
00:12:58,585 --> 00:13:03,646
to be fair and on the flip side we make sure that our world is utterly unfair and exciting and

296
00:13:03,646 --> 00:13:05,687
interesting to keep you busy and occupied.

297
00:13:06,446 --> 00:13:07,887
So how do we actually go about doing that?

298
00:13:07,887 --> 00:13:09,670
What are we aiming to do?

299
00:13:09,670 --> 00:13:11,632
How do we do this, especially in the context

300
00:13:11,632 --> 00:13:14,055
of a narrative adventure game type thingy?

301
00:13:14,055 --> 00:13:17,019
Well, I have three, you know, rule of three.

302
00:13:17,019 --> 00:13:18,541
I have three things, three ideas.

303
00:13:18,541 --> 00:13:23,487
Firstly, decisions should always at least appear

304
00:13:23,487 --> 00:13:25,170
to change the game state.

305
00:13:25,917 --> 00:13:29,638
Because if they don't, then the choice you made didn't really happen.

306
00:13:29,638 --> 00:13:31,679
If you want people to be thinking, yikes, what have I done?

307
00:13:31,679 --> 00:13:34,580
Then they have to feel like they've done something.

308
00:13:34,580 --> 00:13:36,580
So if they, for example, ask a question of an NPC

309
00:13:36,580 --> 00:13:40,482
and then have the option to ask the same question again,

310
00:13:40,482 --> 00:13:43,342
that first asking never really happened.

311
00:13:43,342 --> 00:13:45,103
So people would say, oh, I didn't do that.

312
00:13:45,103 --> 00:13:47,444
That didn't really occur.

313
00:13:47,444 --> 00:13:48,244
So you can't do that.

314
00:13:48,244 --> 00:13:50,985
We have to make sure that if you ask someone something,

315
00:13:50,985 --> 00:13:52,345
then you don't get to ask it again.

316
00:13:53,260 --> 00:13:57,524
Similarly, when I ask someone something and I come back to a dialogue hub,

317
00:13:57,524 --> 00:14:01,028
I don't want to see the same two exact questions that I saw a moment ago,

318
00:14:01,028 --> 00:14:03,790
because then it feels like nothing has changed in the game state.

319
00:14:03,790 --> 00:14:08,635
Even if you superficially do nothing but change the text of the options a little bit

320
00:14:08,635 --> 00:14:11,097
to reflect the conversation has moved on a touch.

321
00:14:11,791 --> 00:14:14,892
That's fine, but I want to feel like time is always moving

322
00:14:14,892 --> 00:14:17,994
because that way I can feel like what I'm doing

323
00:14:17,994 --> 00:14:19,995
may or may not be the thing that caused me

324
00:14:19,995 --> 00:14:21,495
to be in the situation I'm in right now.

325
00:14:21,495 --> 00:14:24,077
I don't want to see the system saying,

326
00:14:24,077 --> 00:14:25,637
your input has been discarded.

327
00:14:25,637 --> 00:14:25,737
Cool.

328
00:14:25,737 --> 00:14:30,380
I like to take that further with our games.

329
00:14:30,380 --> 00:14:31,740
Generally, if you're rude to characters,

330
00:14:31,740 --> 00:14:34,201
they'll get grumpy and they'll eventually wander off.

331
00:14:34,201 --> 00:14:34,942
Things like that.

332
00:14:34,942 --> 00:14:36,662
That sort of stuff is much better.

333
00:14:36,662 --> 00:14:38,623
Arguably, that is a change to the game state,

334
00:14:38,623 --> 00:14:40,084
but it might be quite a subtle one.

335
00:14:40,893 --> 00:14:44,356
Secondly, there should always be a way forward and no getting stuck.

336
00:14:44,356 --> 00:14:49,441
I don't mean that it's ever okay or that anyone thinks it's okay

337
00:14:49,441 --> 00:14:53,005
for a game to let you get to a point where you cannot possibly continue.

338
00:14:53,005 --> 00:14:54,686
I don't mean that kind of stuckness.

339
00:14:54,686 --> 00:14:57,529
I mean rather that I don't ever want the player to experience the sensation

340
00:14:57,529 --> 00:14:59,431
that they know they're supposed to get through this door,

341
00:14:59,431 --> 00:15:00,292
but they don't know how to do it.

342
00:15:01,612 --> 00:15:05,136
Because, obviously, as soon as that happens,

343
00:15:05,136 --> 00:15:06,997
and it happens in adventure games all the time,

344
00:15:06,997 --> 00:15:08,399
they're not thinking, yikes, what have I done?

345
00:15:08,399 --> 00:15:11,041
They're thinking, what am I supposed to do next?

346
00:15:11,041 --> 00:15:12,923
And players will drop back to that,

347
00:15:12,923 --> 00:15:15,045
because it's the lowest energy state for them.

348
00:15:15,045 --> 00:15:16,406
If you give them the opportunity to decide

349
00:15:16,406 --> 00:15:18,808
that it's your fault, not their fault,

350
00:15:18,808 --> 00:15:20,170
that they can't get through this door,

351
00:15:20,170 --> 00:15:22,472
then they will take that opportunity very gratefully,

352
00:15:22,472 --> 00:15:24,634
and then they will tell you that your game sucks.

353
00:15:24,634 --> 00:15:25,455
And that is your problem.

354
00:15:25,455 --> 00:15:25,675
Thirdly,

355
00:15:29,105 --> 00:15:31,346
There should be no empty spaces.

356
00:15:31,346 --> 00:15:32,667
There should be no dead air.

357
00:15:32,667 --> 00:15:36,269
I don't think it should be possible to explore an area

358
00:15:36,269 --> 00:15:38,650
in a narrative game with nothing in it that you can do.

359
00:15:38,650 --> 00:15:40,651
This happens in adventure games all the time

360
00:15:40,651 --> 00:15:41,472
when you're backtracking

361
00:15:41,472 --> 00:15:42,732
because you're worried that you missed something,

362
00:15:42,732 --> 00:15:44,353
but actually you're going through an environment

363
00:15:44,353 --> 00:15:45,514
which you've completely cased

364
00:15:45,514 --> 00:15:46,355
and there's nothing left in it.

365
00:15:46,898 --> 00:15:49,422
The problem is when I do that, time stops moving.

366
00:15:49,422 --> 00:15:51,705
As a player, I don't think, yikes, what have I done?

367
00:15:51,705 --> 00:15:52,987
Because I haven't done anything.

368
00:15:52,987 --> 00:15:54,770
I just wander around an empty room.

369
00:15:54,770 --> 00:15:56,813
That same is true if that empty room has a couple of

370
00:15:56,813 --> 00:15:58,875
characters in it who are sitting there waiting for me

371
00:15:58,875 --> 00:16:01,179
to talk to them, but otherwise doing nothing.

372
00:16:01,179 --> 00:16:01,219
So.

373
00:16:03,611 --> 00:16:05,331
This seems like quite an odd list.

374
00:16:05,331 --> 00:16:07,992
This is a curious design shopping list

375
00:16:07,992 --> 00:16:09,332
that doesn't appear to have very much to do

376
00:16:09,332 --> 00:16:11,673
with player freedom, but I argue that these things

377
00:16:11,673 --> 00:16:14,534
are absolutely important to creating this sense

378
00:16:14,534 --> 00:16:17,154
of being in the moment, which is the thing that we want.

379
00:16:17,154 --> 00:16:19,275
And also they are things which pretty much

380
00:16:19,275 --> 00:16:21,915
every single adventure game ever made

381
00:16:21,915 --> 00:16:24,196
has failed all three of them all the time.

382
00:16:24,196 --> 00:16:24,456
Okay, so.

383
00:16:29,835 --> 00:16:31,816
Have any of them done well at all?

384
00:16:31,816 --> 00:16:33,698
Is there anything nice we can say about games

385
00:16:33,698 --> 00:16:34,919
that have existed in the past?

386
00:16:34,919 --> 00:16:37,481
Yes, I have a couple of games that I think are brilliant

387
00:16:37,481 --> 00:16:38,622
and will do this really well.

388
00:16:38,622 --> 00:16:41,565
Anyone who ever heard me talk about games before ever,

389
00:16:41,565 --> 00:16:43,426
apologies, this is gonna be really the most boring

390
00:16:43,426 --> 00:16:46,469
and predictable two slides you've ever seen.

391
00:16:46,469 --> 00:16:48,510
The first game is The Last Express from 1997.

392
00:16:48,510 --> 00:16:49,551
I think I've put a photo of The Last Express

393
00:16:49,551 --> 00:16:51,073
in every talk I've ever done, ever.

394
00:16:51,073 --> 00:16:52,654
It is the greatest game ever made.

395
00:16:52,654 --> 00:16:54,035
If you haven't played it, it's,

396
00:16:54,035 --> 00:16:56,037
well, if you haven't played it, you're a bloody fool.

397
00:16:57,207 --> 00:17:03,089
It's a real-time, always moving forward, train game in which the clock never stops,

398
00:17:03,089 --> 00:17:06,750
the characters move around on their own schedules, they ignore you if you don't do anything with

399
00:17:06,750 --> 00:17:07,271
them.

400
00:17:07,271 --> 00:17:12,712
It's extremely easy to miss opportunities in it, but it is also extremely good at setting

401
00:17:12,712 --> 00:17:16,293
up opportunities for you to cleverly use that system and find things to do it.

402
00:17:16,293 --> 00:17:17,714
But it's not a systematic game.

403
00:17:18,762 --> 00:17:23,144
Rather, it's a game that offers lots of interesting changes of context throughout its narrative.

404
00:17:23,144 --> 00:17:27,346
It's also the best piece of writing that any video game has ever produced, and it's never

405
00:17:27,346 --> 00:17:29,327
been even approached, let alone bettered.

406
00:17:30,315 --> 00:17:32,195
But it's far too tight.

407
00:17:32,195 --> 00:17:33,996
It doesn't know how to handle this freedom.

408
00:17:33,996 --> 00:17:36,657
It has lots of fail states where there's nothing you can do

409
00:17:36,657 --> 00:17:38,758
but replay and start the section again.

410
00:17:38,758 --> 00:17:41,099
And quite often, the correct way through one

411
00:17:41,099 --> 00:17:43,219
of its fail states is utterly cryptic and hidden.

412
00:17:43,219 --> 00:17:45,740
It doesn't know how to solve that problem.

413
00:17:45,740 --> 00:17:47,421
That's a very hard problem.

414
00:17:47,421 --> 00:17:48,561
But it's a very valid problem.

415
00:17:48,561 --> 00:17:49,402
It's a very good problem.

416
00:17:49,402 --> 00:17:50,882
And it is a fantastic piece of work.

417
00:17:50,882 --> 00:17:54,224
The second game that I want to mention

418
00:17:54,224 --> 00:17:55,544
is the Blade Runner adventure game.

419
00:17:58,094 --> 00:18:01,795
which is famous because it randomized who was a replicant

420
00:18:01,795 --> 00:18:03,216
and who wasn't every time you started.

421
00:18:03,216 --> 00:18:06,136
But that's really the least interesting thing about it

422
00:18:06,136 --> 00:18:07,337
because you only play it once, right?

423
00:18:07,337 --> 00:18:08,317
So it's an adventure game.

424
00:18:08,317 --> 00:18:09,377
So who cares?

425
00:18:09,377 --> 00:18:11,498
You're never gonna know.

426
00:18:11,498 --> 00:18:12,798
What it actually is though,

427
00:18:12,798 --> 00:18:15,319
is a really good example of a detective game.

428
00:18:16,491 --> 00:18:19,394
You go to a location when it is narratively meaningful.

429
00:18:19,394 --> 00:18:21,796
You don't get to go there unless it's narratively meaningful.

430
00:18:21,796 --> 00:18:24,999
Your player always has a good reason to be there.

431
00:18:24,999 --> 00:18:26,160
They case it looking for evidence

432
00:18:26,160 --> 00:18:27,882
or to discover whatever it is they want to find.

433
00:18:27,882 --> 00:18:29,303
When they found everything,

434
00:18:29,303 --> 00:18:31,485
it's clearly telegraphed that maybe now you should go.

435
00:18:31,485 --> 00:18:33,867
And once you go, there's never any reason to go back.

436
00:18:33,867 --> 00:18:36,169
It's very good at removing dead air from the game.

437
00:18:36,169 --> 00:18:39,092
Actually, you can go back, but I have no idea why,

438
00:18:39,092 --> 00:18:40,874
because there's never any reason to do that.

439
00:18:41,833 --> 00:18:45,154
Meanwhile, as you find people and suspects,

440
00:18:45,154 --> 00:18:46,875
well, they might be replicants, they might not be,

441
00:18:46,875 --> 00:18:48,295
you might let them go, you might shoot them,

442
00:18:48,295 --> 00:18:49,396
you might arrest them,

443
00:18:49,396 --> 00:18:51,256
and it copes with that dynamic story state.

444
00:18:51,256 --> 00:18:53,377
It doesn't give you a lot of opportunity

445
00:18:53,377 --> 00:18:55,178
to branch the narrative, but when it does,

446
00:18:55,178 --> 00:18:56,318
it tries to compensate for it

447
00:18:56,318 --> 00:18:58,919
and make sure there's always something for you to do next.

448
00:18:58,919 --> 00:19:01,340
It does a really good job of stopping you from getting stuck

449
00:19:01,340 --> 00:19:02,701
by presenting you instead with,

450
00:19:02,701 --> 00:19:04,922
here are some interesting options and we will handle them.

451
00:19:06,039 --> 00:19:11,862
But it's far too broad, it's far too ambitious, it randomises bizarre things it doesn't need to,

452
00:19:11,862 --> 00:19:16,664
it produces... it's got the weirdest dialogue system in the entire world in that it has choices

453
00:19:16,664 --> 00:19:20,426
but it chooses the choice for you automatically based on a setting in the menu which says what

454
00:19:20,426 --> 00:19:24,368
kind of cop do you want to be. So like, I mean you don't find that setting until you've fiddled

455
00:19:24,368 --> 00:19:27,790
around with it for a while but you can be like the jokey cop or the moody cop or the director's

456
00:19:27,790 --> 00:19:30,431
cut cop who says whatever line they thought was best.

457
00:19:32,034 --> 00:19:36,554
it's possible to get stuck because the game chooses the wrong dialogue option for you.

458
00:19:37,890 --> 00:19:40,211
which is just, it's bizarre, anyway.

459
00:19:40,211 --> 00:19:42,391
It's far too ambitious, it wasn't properly tested,

460
00:19:42,391 --> 00:19:43,532
most playthroughs dry up,

461
00:19:43,532 --> 00:19:45,833
there's just nothing more to do anymore.

462
00:19:45,833 --> 00:19:46,773
And those of you who've played it,

463
00:19:46,773 --> 00:19:48,634
which is probably not all that many anymore

464
00:19:48,634 --> 00:19:50,314
because it's quite hard to play now,

465
00:19:50,314 --> 00:19:52,455
the event on the left is the point

466
00:19:52,455 --> 00:19:53,976
at which you can branch the narrative

467
00:19:53,976 --> 00:19:55,756
into being a replicant sympathizer,

468
00:19:55,756 --> 00:19:58,257
which opens up an entire raft of endings,

469
00:19:58,257 --> 00:20:00,858
but only if you perform what can only be described

470
00:20:00,858 --> 00:20:02,659
as an invisible quick time event.

471
00:20:03,219 --> 00:20:06,021
which is one of the worst pieces of design I've ever seen.

472
00:20:06,021 --> 00:20:10,485
But it is a very robust example of how to use your map

473
00:20:10,485 --> 00:20:13,487
as part of your narrative progression.

474
00:20:13,487 --> 00:20:17,470
So, what are we gonna do with all this?

475
00:20:17,470 --> 00:20:18,831
How are we gonna go about this?

476
00:20:18,831 --> 00:20:18,951
Well.

477
00:20:19,760 --> 00:20:25,204
I'm a great believer in games starting with human beings and starting with tools.

478
00:20:25,204 --> 00:20:30,168
As I said, Ink, our scripting language, is a philosophical statement, and its statement

479
00:20:30,168 --> 00:20:33,551
is that the people writing your game should be able to get on and do that without worrying

480
00:20:33,551 --> 00:20:35,112
about computers too much.

481
00:20:35,112 --> 00:20:40,156
So I want to start our process with working out how we're going to author interactivity

482
00:20:40,156 --> 00:20:42,237
in a way that supports freedom.

483
00:20:42,237 --> 00:20:42,278
So.

484
00:20:45,055 --> 00:20:48,838
Our previous games, 80 Days, Sorcery, are basically branching trees.

485
00:20:48,838 --> 00:20:51,159
They're quite complicated, self-referential branching trees.

486
00:20:51,159 --> 00:20:54,181
They self-reference each other a lot to make sure that they're dynamic and responsive,

487
00:20:54,181 --> 00:20:58,724
but fundamentally they start here, they wibble around, and they get to an end and they stop.

488
00:20:58,724 --> 00:21:00,005
There's only so much you can do with that.

489
00:21:00,507 --> 00:21:02,688
And it's not great when you're arranged in a 3D world,

490
00:21:02,688 --> 00:21:04,269
because you might bounce from prop to prop.

491
00:21:04,269 --> 00:21:05,450
You might want to engage with this,

492
00:21:05,450 --> 00:21:06,150
and then engage with that,

493
00:21:06,150 --> 00:21:07,031
and then come back to here,

494
00:21:07,031 --> 00:21:08,031
and then go over there.

495
00:21:08,031 --> 00:21:10,333
That doesn't look or feel like a branching tree

496
00:21:10,333 --> 00:21:11,233
in the slightest.

497
00:21:11,233 --> 00:21:12,254
So what do we do instead?

498
00:21:12,254 --> 00:21:15,176
Well, we took an approach that we prototyped a little bit

499
00:21:15,176 --> 00:21:19,018
during the sorcery games of a system

500
00:21:19,018 --> 00:21:22,040
which offers content on the fly if it's appropriate.

501
00:21:22,040 --> 00:21:26,223
We've made all of our content atomic,

502
00:21:26,223 --> 00:21:26,903
by which I mean.

503
00:21:27,808 --> 00:21:30,629
Every action, including dialogue, is a little blob of content.

504
00:21:30,629 --> 00:21:32,670
It sits on its own somewhere in the code.

505
00:21:32,670 --> 00:21:35,631
Every blob is gated by preconditions.

506
00:21:35,631 --> 00:21:38,572
A precondition is just a piece of logic that says

507
00:21:38,572 --> 00:21:41,894
this is what you need for this bit of content to be appropriate,

508
00:21:41,894 --> 00:21:43,014
to be meaningful right now.

509
00:21:43,014 --> 00:21:46,976
And of course, the preconditions must be satisfied

510
00:21:46,976 --> 00:21:49,397
for the content to be allowed to be surfaced by the game.

511
00:21:50,082 --> 00:21:52,443
This design is drawn from Inform 7.

512
00:21:52,443 --> 00:21:56,264
I think it was the rule-based design used there,

513
00:21:56,264 --> 00:21:57,864
which was the work of Graham Nelson,

514
00:21:57,864 --> 00:21:59,785
Emily Short, Andrew Plotkin, possibly others.

515
00:21:59,785 --> 00:22:03,966
But I've never seen it used in an adventure game,

516
00:22:03,966 --> 00:22:05,946
to my knowledge, anyway.

517
00:22:05,946 --> 00:22:07,307
So we do all of this in ink.

518
00:22:07,307 --> 00:22:09,807
Ink looks roughly like this.

519
00:22:09,807 --> 00:22:11,168
This is a shot from our demo,

520
00:22:11,168 --> 00:22:13,348
so there's a couple of options on this shrine thing.

521
00:22:13,348 --> 00:22:15,569
There are three blobs of content

522
00:22:15,569 --> 00:22:17,109
in the content bucket of the game.

523
00:22:17,843 --> 00:22:20,064
Those preconditions are the little things in curly braces.

524
00:22:20,064 --> 00:22:22,926
The top two, all of those preconditions are being satisfied.

525
00:22:22,926 --> 00:22:25,987
So those options are surfaced and you can see them attached to the pillar.

526
00:22:25,987 --> 00:22:28,628
The bottom one is not being surfaced.

527
00:22:28,628 --> 00:22:30,769
Something in that must not be true.

528
00:22:30,769 --> 00:22:33,550
In this case, it's I've recently been zapped by this thing.

529
00:22:33,550 --> 00:22:36,571
And so the condition not recently zapped by shrine fails.

530
00:22:36,571 --> 00:22:37,972
So it doesn't allow it to surface.

531
00:22:37,972 --> 00:22:39,712
And that's what I mean by atomic content.

532
00:22:39,712 --> 00:22:41,853
This isn't a branching tree.

533
00:22:41,853 --> 00:22:43,294
It's just a set of things that might happen.

534
00:22:43,294 --> 00:22:45,575
These are brilliant.

535
00:22:46,225 --> 00:22:48,086
They're really, really, really powerful,

536
00:22:48,086 --> 00:22:51,409
because you can just keep loading stuff onto them.

537
00:22:51,409 --> 00:22:53,130
So the types of preconditions that we use,

538
00:22:53,130 --> 00:22:54,991
I'll just catalog them very quickly.

539
00:22:54,991 --> 00:22:57,532
The world state, obviously, where are you,

540
00:22:57,532 --> 00:22:59,113
what can you see, what can you touch,

541
00:22:59,113 --> 00:23:00,875
what have you got, what's open, what's closed,

542
00:23:00,875 --> 00:23:01,875
all the normal kind of things.

543
00:23:01,875 --> 00:23:04,557
So we do some state tracking, we use trigger volumes,

544
00:23:04,557 --> 00:23:05,798
we use raycasts, whatever.

545
00:23:06,543 --> 00:23:12,426
The knowledge state. I talked about this quite at length at last year's GDC, so I won't recap the system that we use,

546
00:23:12,426 --> 00:23:15,748
but we track everything that the player knows and everything that they need to know,

547
00:23:15,748 --> 00:23:18,990
and what leads their following using chains of knowledge.

548
00:23:18,990 --> 00:23:23,673
Heaven's Vault has about, I don't know, 1,500 knowledge states or something, and we're constantly tracking that.

549
00:23:24,154 --> 00:23:28,735
We also, more interestingly, check what's just happened,

550
00:23:28,735 --> 00:23:31,315
both in the world and in the knowledge state.

551
00:23:31,315 --> 00:23:32,256
So you can say things like,

552
00:23:32,256 --> 00:23:34,076
have you recently learned a fact about this?

553
00:23:34,076 --> 00:23:36,077
Have you recently discovered that?

554
00:23:36,077 --> 00:23:37,237
Have you recently discovered this,

555
00:23:37,237 --> 00:23:38,517
but you haven't yet discovered that?

556
00:23:38,517 --> 00:23:41,858
In which case, it might be a good idea to do this.

557
00:23:41,858 --> 00:23:44,799
We do that at the ink level using the turns since query.

558
00:23:45,891 --> 00:23:47,311
So I said preconditions are great.

559
00:23:47,311 --> 00:23:49,152
I said atomic content is great.

560
00:23:49,152 --> 00:23:51,252
You're probably all just going, I don't really even see

561
00:23:51,252 --> 00:23:53,152
why that would be the case.

562
00:23:53,152 --> 00:23:55,153
So let me try and outline the benefits.

563
00:23:55,153 --> 00:23:57,793
And it's all human.

564
00:23:57,793 --> 00:24:02,014
I can author this stuff in a really responsive way.

565
00:24:02,014 --> 00:24:04,954
If I want to add an action to the game, or I want to add a

566
00:24:04,954 --> 00:24:07,015
line of dialogue to the game, I want to give the

567
00:24:07,015 --> 00:24:09,595
protagonist the ability to ask a particular question, I

568
00:24:09,595 --> 00:24:10,955
simply write that question down.

569
00:24:10,955 --> 00:24:13,456
And I say, when is this question appropriate?

570
00:24:13,456 --> 00:24:14,676
Well, to ask this question.

571
00:24:15,496 --> 00:24:17,718
I need to know, she needs to know this fact.

572
00:24:17,718 --> 00:24:20,220
So, okay, test one, do you know that fact?

573
00:24:20,220 --> 00:24:21,922
This question becomes redundant

574
00:24:21,922 --> 00:24:23,984
if she already knows the answer.

575
00:24:23,984 --> 00:24:25,185
So, second precondition,

576
00:24:25,185 --> 00:24:26,646
do you not already know the answer?

577
00:24:26,646 --> 00:24:27,727
Great, bung that in.

578
00:24:27,727 --> 00:24:29,268
Wait, no, this question doesn't make sense

579
00:24:29,268 --> 00:24:31,010
if I'm in the dark, because in the dark,

580
00:24:31,010 --> 00:24:32,912
I don't want to ask questions about

581
00:24:32,912 --> 00:24:34,353
some random fact in the story.

582
00:24:34,353 --> 00:24:36,515
So if you're in the dark, that's a fail state,

583
00:24:36,515 --> 00:24:37,356
and so on and so forth.

584
00:24:37,356 --> 00:24:39,057
You just bung in all the preconditions.

585
00:24:39,057 --> 00:24:40,298
Wap, wap, wap, wap, wap, wap, wap, wap.

586
00:24:41,376 --> 00:24:46,940
And under every other circumstance where all of these things are met, fine, this thing might be what the game does.

587
00:24:46,940 --> 00:24:51,383
You chuck it in a bucket, there are 60 things in the bucket, the game will pick something and it will always make sense.

588
00:24:51,383 --> 00:24:55,726
And if it doesn't make sense, well that's fine, you just put another precondition on it.

589
00:24:55,726 --> 00:24:57,047
Or you prioritize it.

590
00:24:57,047 --> 00:25:01,831
And the game will give you something sensible and something dynamic and something that moves things forward.

591
00:25:03,377 --> 00:25:05,598
What I'm trying to say is that non-linear flows

592
00:25:05,598 --> 00:25:07,120
arise naturally from the system.

593
00:25:07,120 --> 00:25:08,501
You don't have to author them.

594
00:25:08,501 --> 00:25:10,222
You don't need a branching tree to ensure

595
00:25:10,222 --> 00:25:11,623
that your game is non-linear.

596
00:25:11,623 --> 00:25:13,325
It can't be linear.

597
00:25:13,325 --> 00:25:15,546
It's effectively a deck of cards that you've shuffled

598
00:25:15,546 --> 00:25:16,988
and you're dealing them out,

599
00:25:16,988 --> 00:25:19,470
except that cards are only ever cards which are relevant.

600
00:25:19,470 --> 00:25:20,931
It's a bit like the authoring structure

601
00:25:20,931 --> 00:25:23,553
that Lee Alexander outlined for Reigns, right?

602
00:25:23,553 --> 00:25:26,655
That's an atomized set of content with preconditions

603
00:25:26,655 --> 00:25:29,097
that say when a card is allowed to be released or not.

604
00:25:29,097 --> 00:25:30,218
It's exactly the same idea.

605
00:25:30,819 --> 00:25:36,001
Only ours is very, very flexible in terms of what that content can be,

606
00:25:36,001 --> 00:25:39,142
because it can be anything, literally any action in the entire game.

607
00:25:39,142 --> 00:25:42,823
So, obviously there are issues.

608
00:25:42,823 --> 00:25:48,165
Well, the biggest issue, I hope, is probably what you think it is,

609
00:25:48,165 --> 00:25:52,367
if you've been sort of following the idea of what this is,

610
00:25:52,367 --> 00:25:54,828
that it's incredibly annoying to write.

611
00:25:55,808 --> 00:25:57,489
It's incredibly repetitive.

612
00:25:57,489 --> 00:25:59,851
Am I really saying that on every single option

613
00:25:59,851 --> 00:26:01,572
in the entire game, there are 20,000 lines of dialogue

614
00:26:01,572 --> 00:26:04,433
in this game already, I have to say,

615
00:26:04,433 --> 00:26:05,454
are you in the dark?

616
00:26:05,454 --> 00:26:07,195
Don't say this if you're in the dark.

617
00:26:07,195 --> 00:26:08,335
Have you just stubbed your toe?

618
00:26:08,335 --> 00:26:09,816
Don't say this if you've stubbed your toe.

619
00:26:09,816 --> 00:26:11,357
Are you having an argument with Six?

620
00:26:11,357 --> 00:26:11,997
Don't be nice to him.

621
00:26:11,997 --> 00:26:14,038
On every single line of dialogue,

622
00:26:14,038 --> 00:26:16,040
do I really have to list every single way

623
00:26:16,040 --> 00:26:18,061
that this would be an inappropriate thing to say?

624
00:26:18,061 --> 00:26:19,722
And the answer is sort of, yeah.

625
00:26:20,750 --> 00:26:24,932
I kind of do, because otherwise the game is going to say something stupid,

626
00:26:24,932 --> 00:26:27,654
because it's only a game. It doesn't know.

627
00:26:27,654 --> 00:26:31,677
But this is a problem we can tackle, and it's not even a difficult problem to tackle.

628
00:26:31,677 --> 00:26:36,420
The solution is exactly what a software engineer would tell you the solution was.

629
00:26:36,420 --> 00:26:38,962
We use authoring patterns. In particular, we use scopes.

630
00:26:38,962 --> 00:26:43,905
So all of our content is scoped. So we write in buckets.

631
00:26:43,905 --> 00:26:44,806
We have four buckets.

632
00:26:45,508 --> 00:26:46,569
We have the moment bucket.

633
00:26:46,569 --> 00:26:48,730
This is a thing that's happening right now.

634
00:26:48,730 --> 00:26:50,450
I am talking to you people right now.

635
00:26:50,450 --> 00:26:52,131
So everything that I say to you right now

636
00:26:52,131 --> 00:26:53,992
will be about the topic that I'm talking about,

637
00:26:53,992 --> 00:26:56,713
hopefully, and I won't do some weird Freudian thing.

638
00:26:56,713 --> 00:26:57,933
But I'm not gonna start telling you

639
00:26:57,933 --> 00:26:58,633
about what I had for lunch.

640
00:26:59,559 --> 00:27:02,080
because right now I am just looking at the options

641
00:27:02,080 --> 00:27:04,082
that are available to me in this moment.

642
00:27:04,082 --> 00:27:06,123
So it's great for an argument, it's great for a set piece,

643
00:27:06,123 --> 00:27:07,423
it's great for a conversation, fine.

644
00:27:07,423 --> 00:27:09,144
That's just normal branching trees.

645
00:27:09,144 --> 00:27:11,646
They're little, but they still exist.

646
00:27:11,646 --> 00:27:14,847
If I am not in a moment context, then I'm in a room.

647
00:27:14,847 --> 00:27:17,169
We use rooms as our sort of base level interaction.

648
00:27:17,169 --> 00:27:19,850
So in a room, there are various things I could do.

649
00:27:19,850 --> 00:27:21,231
If I was to come down from the podium,

650
00:27:21,231 --> 00:27:22,912
I could sit on a chair, I could go to the door,

651
00:27:22,912 --> 00:27:24,172
I could take the microphone, whatever.

652
00:27:24,172 --> 00:27:26,093
I could do things within this room.

653
00:27:26,634 --> 00:27:28,595
So when I want to author content for this room,

654
00:27:28,595 --> 00:27:29,856
I put it in the room bucket.

655
00:27:29,856 --> 00:27:32,258
I put it in the hall bucket, and there we go, fill it up.

656
00:27:32,258 --> 00:27:35,000
If I have an idea for something I might do out in the hall,

657
00:27:35,000 --> 00:27:37,241
well, I find that bucket, the room of the hall,

658
00:27:37,241 --> 00:27:38,782
and I put it in there instead.

659
00:27:38,782 --> 00:27:40,904
So that scopes it geographically for me.

660
00:27:40,904 --> 00:27:43,026
And we have some markup to help Unity know

661
00:27:43,026 --> 00:27:44,206
what prop is this attached to.

662
00:27:44,206 --> 00:27:44,767
Can you see it?

663
00:27:44,767 --> 00:27:45,487
Can you touch it?

664
00:27:45,487 --> 00:27:46,068
That kind of thing.

665
00:27:47,292 --> 00:27:48,493
That includes dialogue.

666
00:27:48,493 --> 00:27:50,535
Most importantly, that includes dialogue.

667
00:27:50,535 --> 00:27:52,016
There are things I might want to say

668
00:27:52,016 --> 00:27:53,497
because I'm in this room,

669
00:27:53,497 --> 00:27:55,759
but I don't want to say if I'm on the street outside.

670
00:27:55,759 --> 00:27:58,061
So that allows Elle, our protagonist,

671
00:27:58,061 --> 00:27:59,802
to remove conversation options

672
00:27:59,802 --> 00:28:01,203
and gain conversation options

673
00:28:01,203 --> 00:28:03,525
based on where she happens to be standing in the world.

674
00:28:03,525 --> 00:28:03,745
Fine.

675
00:28:04,806 --> 00:28:11,007
If there is nothing in the room that she wants to talk about, then we drop back to episode level content.

676
00:28:11,007 --> 00:28:14,848
So we have another bucket. This is across a series of rooms that are relevant.

677
00:28:14,848 --> 00:28:19,609
So my episode at the moment is being in San Francisco and being a little bit jet-lagged but mostly okay,

678
00:28:19,609 --> 00:28:22,390
and my dialogue is all about being in San Francisco.

679
00:28:22,390 --> 00:28:24,390
And I can say these lines of dialogue like,

680
00:28:24,390 --> 00:28:25,910
gosh, isn't San Francisco a lovely city?

681
00:28:25,910 --> 00:28:29,151
Or, gosh, you really do have a poverty problem, guys, you want to sort that out.

682
00:28:29,471 --> 00:28:32,194
and I can say that anywhere in San Francisco,

683
00:28:32,194 --> 00:28:34,596
and it's relevant and it's appropriate and it's apropos,

684
00:28:34,596 --> 00:28:36,798
so long as there's not something I should be saying

685
00:28:36,798 --> 00:28:39,160
in the room context, like where's the coffee,

686
00:28:39,160 --> 00:28:40,781
and so long as I'm not in the middle of a moment

687
00:28:40,781 --> 00:28:42,103
of delivering a lecture to you guys

688
00:28:42,103 --> 00:28:43,584
about something else completely.

689
00:28:43,584 --> 00:28:43,724
Fine.

690
00:28:43,724 --> 00:28:49,409
Okay, beyond that is the game scope.

691
00:28:50,819 --> 00:28:52,881
all the other things that she might say,

692
00:28:52,881 --> 00:28:53,982
all the things that could be relevant

693
00:28:53,982 --> 00:28:55,063
at any given time at all.

694
00:28:55,063 --> 00:28:58,466
These are the things where she can synthesize information.

695
00:28:58,466 --> 00:28:59,547
She can reflect on information

696
00:28:59,547 --> 00:29:00,908
from multiple places in the game.

697
00:29:00,908 --> 00:29:02,790
She can draw things together.

698
00:29:02,790 --> 00:29:05,653
She can bridge one episode to another episode.

699
00:29:05,653 --> 00:29:08,676
And that basically sits at the bottom of the hierarchy

700
00:29:08,676 --> 00:29:10,317
because it's the one that can come up anytime.

701
00:29:10,317 --> 00:29:13,340
So the content is shadowed,

702
00:29:13,340 --> 00:29:15,021
each scope shadowing the next.

703
00:29:16,837 --> 00:29:18,758
And this is brilliant, right?

704
00:29:18,758 --> 00:29:21,539
This is really brilliant because it partly removes

705
00:29:21,539 --> 00:29:22,699
huge amounts of the preconditions

706
00:29:22,699 --> 00:29:25,320
because the scope just says this is the scope,

707
00:29:25,320 --> 00:29:26,460
so it's fine.

708
00:29:26,460 --> 00:29:29,101
It has a prioritization system,

709
00:29:29,101 --> 00:29:30,661
but for me as a human being,

710
00:29:30,661 --> 00:29:33,442
it's very easy for me to decide where to put my content.

711
00:29:33,442 --> 00:29:35,603
If I'm writing a dialogue about the history of robots

712
00:29:35,603 --> 00:29:37,503
in the universe, that's game scope, fine.

713
00:29:37,503 --> 00:29:40,464
If I'm writing a line of dialogue about the planet I'm on,

714
00:29:40,464 --> 00:29:41,504
that's episode scope.

715
00:29:41,504 --> 00:29:43,465
If I'm writing the line of dialogue about whether

716
00:29:43,465 --> 00:29:45,546
this door is gonna be openable, that's room scope.

717
00:29:45,546 --> 00:29:46,286
This is trivial.

718
00:29:46,806 --> 00:29:49,647
It takes no time at all to work out where you're going to put your bit of content.

719
00:29:49,647 --> 00:29:51,688
You just bung it straight in and move forward.

720
00:29:51,688 --> 00:29:55,470
So you get all the benefits of additive, atomized content

721
00:29:55,470 --> 00:29:57,771
without having to worry too much about structure.

722
00:29:57,771 --> 00:30:01,312
Well, in fact, without having to worry at all about structure,

723
00:30:01,312 --> 00:30:04,074
and that's the other big problem,

724
00:30:04,074 --> 00:30:06,074
when you atomize all your content,

725
00:30:06,074 --> 00:30:08,515
you don't have a way of enforcing structure,

726
00:30:08,515 --> 00:30:10,917
by which I mean long-term plot structure.

727
00:30:11,719 --> 00:30:14,841
To say at the beginning of the game people should be very sort of kind to each other

728
00:30:14,841 --> 00:30:18,564
and by the end of the game they should say big dramatic exciting things because most

729
00:30:18,564 --> 00:30:21,827
of your content doesn't know when it's happening unless you write a precondition to tell it

730
00:30:21,827 --> 00:30:22,728
when it's happening.

731
00:30:22,728 --> 00:30:23,368
It can get very messy.

732
00:30:24,465 --> 00:30:27,106
So the one thing that we needed to add to this system,

733
00:30:27,106 --> 00:30:29,727
this all works, it's fine, it's running,

734
00:30:29,727 --> 00:30:32,868
was something to enforce long-term narrative structure

735
00:30:32,868 --> 00:30:35,069
because we do want that.

736
00:30:35,069 --> 00:30:37,390
So I said earlier that the system is a little bit like

737
00:30:37,390 --> 00:30:38,550
the system in Reigns.

738
00:30:38,550 --> 00:30:40,451
If you think about the way Reigns works,

739
00:30:40,451 --> 00:30:41,752
you die and then you loop back

740
00:30:41,752 --> 00:30:43,272
and that's its long-term narrative structure.

741
00:30:43,272 --> 00:30:45,553
It's built in these little loops.

742
00:30:45,553 --> 00:30:47,574
We basically do the same thing

743
00:30:47,574 --> 00:30:49,915
except without dying and resetting you,

744
00:30:49,915 --> 00:30:51,076
but instead moving you forwards

