00:40:50,719 --> 00:40:53,400
of things can I have in a dead man's coat? Well, I can have a laundry chit.

990
00:40:53,860 --> 00:40:56,060
I can have a matchbook from a jazz club.

991
00:40:56,060 --> 00:40:57,761
I can have a ticket for the boat.

992
00:40:57,761 --> 00:40:59,481
Those are all locations in my world.

993
00:40:59,481 --> 00:41:01,962
I probably can't have a Kalashnikov.

994
00:41:01,962 --> 00:41:03,482
And I certainly can't have a tiger skin rug.

995
00:41:03,482 --> 00:41:06,643
So don't generate those things.

996
00:41:06,643 --> 00:41:08,083
I say, what does the story need?

997
00:41:08,083 --> 00:41:09,564
Well, right now I really want the player

998
00:41:09,564 --> 00:41:10,584
to go to this laundromat.

999
00:41:10,584 --> 00:41:11,644
You should see how they smell.

1000
00:41:11,644 --> 00:41:12,624
Their shoes look dirty.

1001
00:41:12,624 --> 00:41:13,345
Let's get them there.

1002
00:41:14,365 --> 00:41:15,868
And I said, what does the game need?

1003
00:41:15,868 --> 00:41:17,070
What would be interesting?

1004
00:41:17,070 --> 00:41:19,233
We keep finding laundromat tickets.

1005
00:41:19,233 --> 00:41:21,096
Stop finding laundromat tickets.

1006
00:41:21,096 --> 00:41:23,340
Find something that isn't a laundromat ticket.

1007
00:41:24,102 --> 00:41:26,104
Okay, we triangulate those three and we say,

1008
00:41:26,104 --> 00:41:27,985
aha, oh wait, I've mixed my metaphors.

1009
00:41:27,985 --> 00:41:29,206
I'm back in archeology now.

1010
00:41:29,206 --> 00:41:31,008
I've found an ancient ring with the seal

1011
00:41:31,008 --> 00:41:32,809
of an unknown king that was dropped here.

1012
00:41:32,809 --> 00:41:34,971
And that's what our protagonist will say.

1013
00:41:34,971 --> 00:41:38,254
It's appropriate because it's a small object

1014
00:41:38,254 --> 00:41:40,436
and I found it in a place where small objects can be found.

1015
00:41:40,436 --> 00:41:42,377
It's what the story needs.

1016
00:41:42,377 --> 00:41:44,759
I want my player to go to this palace.

1017
00:41:44,759 --> 00:41:46,741
So I want to give them an artifact from that palace

1018
00:41:46,741 --> 00:41:48,683
so they can have a narrative reason to go there.

1019
00:41:48,683 --> 00:41:49,383
And it's interesting.

1020
00:41:49,603 --> 00:41:51,865
Because it's an ancient ring with the seal of an unknown king.

1021
00:41:51,865 --> 00:41:54,387
Who doesn't like an ancient ring with the seal of an unknown king?

1022
00:41:54,387 --> 00:41:56,088
Everybody wants one of those.

1023
00:41:56,088 --> 00:42:05,474
So, we glue the narrative together using procedural elements.

1024
00:42:05,474 --> 00:42:08,056
If you're Poirot and you find all the clues,

1025
00:42:08,056 --> 00:42:09,957
at some point the procedural system would say,

1026
00:42:09,957 --> 00:42:11,899
I've got nothing for you.

1027
00:42:11,899 --> 00:42:14,941
And our character will lean down, turn over a rock and say,

1028
00:42:14,941 --> 00:42:17,883
there's something here. Oh, no, no, no, there's nothing.

1029
00:42:17,883 --> 00:42:18,543
And she'll carry on.

1030
00:42:19,938 --> 00:42:22,659
Which is fine, because that player's already got everything they need,

1031
00:42:22,659 --> 00:42:25,920
and they need to stop farming the location and get out of the level.

1032
00:42:25,920 --> 00:42:28,801
That's okay, we haven't even lost them.

1033
00:42:28,801 --> 00:42:29,861
So we've got a ton of benefits.

1034
00:42:29,861 --> 00:42:32,541
There's no need to scour the location.

1035
00:42:32,541 --> 00:42:36,642
I, as the adventure game player in L.A. Noire, do not need to rumble the room,

1036
00:42:36,642 --> 00:42:40,363
because I will find the content I need by looking in the places that are interesting.

1037
00:42:40,363 --> 00:42:41,904
I'll check the cupboard, I'll check under the bed,

1038
00:42:41,904 --> 00:42:45,364
I'll check the wardrobe, I've found a couple of things, I've got a lead, I'm good.

1039
00:42:45,364 --> 00:42:48,585
I don't need to worry that there might have been something in the toilet.

1040
00:42:49,622 --> 00:42:52,004
Whereas when I'm playing LA Noire, I have to worry about that.

1041
00:42:52,004 --> 00:42:52,985
I have to go and check it.

1042
00:42:52,985 --> 00:42:55,467
And then having checked it, I have to check that I really did check it.

1043
00:42:55,467 --> 00:42:58,149
And that's the standard experience of adventure games,

1044
00:42:58,149 --> 00:43:00,771
is you walk into an area, you case it, you case it again.

1045
00:43:00,771 --> 00:43:04,755
And then when you're stuck, you go, oh no, and you case it again.

1046
00:43:04,755 --> 00:43:06,837
And then, variably, you missed something.

1047
00:43:06,837 --> 00:43:08,378
Well, you don't need to do that here.

1048
00:43:08,378 --> 00:43:12,402
The adage is always that things are in the last place you look.

1049
00:43:12,402 --> 00:43:14,023
Well, they are.

1050
00:43:14,023 --> 00:43:14,764
That's where we put them.

1051
00:43:17,771 --> 00:43:21,254
we can control the unlock curve of the entire game.

1052
00:43:21,254 --> 00:43:22,515
We couldn't do that before.

1053
00:43:22,515 --> 00:43:23,576
That was the problem.

1054
00:43:23,576 --> 00:43:25,418
Atomized content meant that we had no way

1055
00:43:25,418 --> 00:43:26,959
of controlling the unlock curve of the game,

1056
00:43:26,959 --> 00:43:28,521
but now I've moved it up into code.

1057
00:43:28,521 --> 00:43:31,143
The procedural evidence generator

1058
00:43:31,143 --> 00:43:34,146
is the thing that decides what locations should I unlock,

1059
00:43:34,146 --> 00:43:34,906
when, how quickly.

1060
00:43:36,132 --> 00:43:37,993
And I can tweak that as much as I like,

1061
00:43:37,993 --> 00:43:42,336
and I affect the entire game by tweaking my generation code.

1062
00:43:42,336 --> 00:43:44,758
And I affect all of the games, regardless of the order

1063
00:43:44,758 --> 00:43:45,958
that you're playing the game in.

1064
00:43:45,958 --> 00:43:48,540
Remember, this is an inherently nonlinear flow.

1065
00:43:48,540 --> 00:43:52,162
But I've got one point of entry to control the unlock curve

1066
00:43:52,162 --> 00:43:55,444
of all possible games without reducing any player freedom,

1067
00:43:55,444 --> 00:43:56,705
without restricting anyone in any way.

1068
00:43:56,705 --> 00:43:58,466
I think that's really clever.

1069
00:43:58,466 --> 00:44:00,047
I think that's really useful.

1070
00:44:00,047 --> 00:44:02,889
And I think it's gonna make Heaven's Vault flow nicely.

1071
00:44:02,889 --> 00:44:04,770
But we won't find out that for another year, at least.

1072
00:44:06,234 --> 00:44:10,543
Best of all, writers do not need to be responsible for balancing the information, because writers

1073
00:44:10,543 --> 00:44:13,930
should not be allowed to be responsible for balancing information, because writers are

1074
00:44:13,930 --> 00:44:15,473
cavalier and they don't understand things.

1075
00:44:15,473 --> 00:44:16,796
I am also a writer.

1076
00:44:18,808 --> 00:44:20,409
They can put in real leads.

1077
00:44:20,409 --> 00:44:22,270
If you want to meet the jazz singer in the laundromat,

1078
00:44:22,270 --> 00:44:23,910
that's fine, write her in,

1079
00:44:23,910 --> 00:44:25,431
let her talk about the jazz club,

1080
00:44:25,431 --> 00:44:26,572
handle the fact that the player

1081
00:44:26,572 --> 00:44:27,832
might already have been there,

1082
00:44:27,832 --> 00:44:28,812
handle the fact that the player

1083
00:44:28,812 --> 00:44:30,413
might not know what a jazz is,

1084
00:44:30,413 --> 00:44:32,354
deal with those possibilities, that's your job.

1085
00:44:32,354 --> 00:44:34,375
The procedural system would say,

1086
00:44:34,375 --> 00:44:36,076
oh, they've got a lead to the jazz club,

1087
00:44:36,076 --> 00:44:38,077
so we don't need to give them as much evidence for that.

1088
00:44:38,077 --> 00:44:40,217
Maybe a single matchbook with the name will be enough

1089
00:44:40,217 --> 00:44:41,478
and they can connect it themselves.

1090
00:44:41,478 --> 00:44:41,618
Fine.

1091
00:44:44,078 --> 00:44:46,501
There's no redundant information, as I said.

1092
00:44:46,501 --> 00:44:48,423
Poirot eventually runs out of stuff.

1093
00:44:48,423 --> 00:44:49,624
You don't have players saying,

1094
00:44:49,624 --> 00:44:52,027
I've come to the jazz club because I've found 15 clues

1095
00:44:52,027 --> 00:44:52,648
to come here.

1096
00:44:52,648 --> 00:44:54,049
I know I need to go to the jazz club.

1097
00:44:54,049 --> 00:44:55,090
I'll go to the jazz club.

1098
00:44:55,090 --> 00:44:57,112
I'm really sorry I haven't been to the jazz club yet.

1099
00:44:57,112 --> 00:44:58,634
That's good.

1100
00:44:58,634 --> 00:44:59,315
That's great.

1101
00:44:59,315 --> 00:45:01,417
We don't have unnecessary clues.

1102
00:45:01,417 --> 00:45:02,939
You have just enough evidence.

1103
00:45:03,635 --> 00:45:05,376
And better players are still rewarded.

1104
00:45:05,376 --> 00:45:06,757
If you follow more interesting leads,

1105
00:45:06,757 --> 00:45:08,518
you can get more authored content,

1106
00:45:08,518 --> 00:45:10,959
you can get more interesting evidence,

1107
00:45:10,959 --> 00:45:12,420
and not the procedural stuff.

1108
00:45:12,420 --> 00:45:13,580
And that's obviously better

1109
00:45:13,580 --> 00:45:15,041
because it's gonna be hand-authored.

1110
00:45:15,041 --> 00:45:15,842
So that's fine too.

1111
00:45:17,135 --> 00:45:21,017
Finally, we can also feed the procedurally generated clues directly back into the narrative

1112
00:45:21,017 --> 00:45:25,079
because we have a precondition-based system, right? That's a lot of long words, what do I mean?

1113
00:45:25,079 --> 00:45:29,881
I mean, if you find the ring of an ancient king, you can take it to a shop that buys rings and sell

1114
00:45:29,881 --> 00:45:35,543
it. You can sell it for a piece of genuine, specific, contentful information in the story.

1115
00:45:35,543 --> 00:45:39,365
If you find a knife, you can use it to cut things. If you find a book, you can open it and you can

1116
00:45:39,365 --> 00:45:44,747
read something from inside it. So we can take procedurally generated items and give them

1117
00:45:44,747 --> 00:45:46,108
narrative detail.

1118
00:45:47,275 --> 00:45:49,556
that narrative detail may or may not ever surface

1119
00:45:49,556 --> 00:45:51,477
because the procedural generation may or may not ever

1120
00:45:51,477 --> 00:45:53,198
generate the correct artifact.

1121
00:45:53,198 --> 00:45:55,479
But I don't care because I've got a big content bucket

1122
00:45:55,479 --> 00:45:56,420
and I just chuck stuff in.

1123
00:45:56,420 --> 00:45:58,521
If I have a joke which only applies

1124
00:45:58,521 --> 00:46:00,822
to knives made of crystal, I'll write it and say,

1125
00:46:00,822 --> 00:46:02,642
if you've got a crystal knife, there's your joke.

1126
00:46:02,642 --> 00:46:03,583
If you don't, nevermind.

1127
00:46:03,583 --> 00:46:06,104
And I can do that and I can keep doing that

1128
00:46:06,104 --> 00:46:08,885
right up until release without breaking the unlock curve,

1129
00:46:08,885 --> 00:46:11,066
without breaking anything in the system.

1130
00:46:11,066 --> 00:46:12,487
I can just keep throwing stuff in.

1131
00:46:13,165 --> 00:46:17,543
In fact, the only problem we really have is the frame rate of the story processing, but that's not my problem, that's Joe's.

1132
00:46:19,553 --> 00:46:24,376
So overall, the game loop for our narrative adventure game thingy with high player freedom looks like this.

1133
00:46:24,376 --> 00:46:30,020
You select an episode, you go into the episode, you do the episode content, you collect procedural leads as and when you need to,

1134
00:46:30,020 --> 00:46:33,082
you exit, you go into the open world, there are available episodes,

1135
00:46:33,082 --> 00:46:37,666
and for players who have completely failed to get anything from any of the episodes,

1136
00:46:37,666 --> 00:46:42,109
you can get a procedural lead inside the open world via some kind of grindy pickup.

1137
00:46:42,109 --> 00:46:44,711
So if you're really useless at story games...

1138
00:46:45,071 --> 00:46:47,752
or you really don't want to find anything or do anything,

1139
00:46:47,752 --> 00:46:50,173
then I have no idea why you're still playing our game,

1140
00:46:50,173 --> 00:46:52,014
but you're grinding your way around the open world,

1141
00:46:52,014 --> 00:46:53,274
collecting procedural leads,

1142
00:46:53,274 --> 00:46:55,275
which seem to be fine for people in The Witcher

1143
00:46:55,275 --> 00:46:57,235
and Horizon Zero Dawn and all those other games

1144
00:46:57,235 --> 00:46:59,296
that make you pick up infinite numbers of flowers

1145
00:46:59,296 --> 00:47:01,197
for no reason whatever.

1146
00:47:01,197 --> 00:47:02,798
So if it works for them, it'll work for us, right?

1147
00:47:02,798 --> 00:47:03,718
And ours a narrative too?

1148
00:47:03,718 --> 00:47:06,539
I don't know, somehow I think those people won't enjoy it,

1149
00:47:06,539 --> 00:47:06,839
but whatever.

1150
00:47:06,839 --> 00:47:07,319
And that's our structure.

1151
00:47:07,319 --> 00:47:07,879
That is our game loop.

1152
00:47:17,707 --> 00:47:20,534
I'm really sorry to subject you to that.

1153
00:47:20,534 --> 00:47:21,797
Right.

1154
00:47:21,797 --> 00:47:24,384
And that's the architectural structure of Heaven's Vault.

1155
00:47:24,384 --> 00:47:26,649
That's how we're doing what we're doing.

1156
00:47:27,455 --> 00:47:29,015
At this point, we've built one demo level.

1157
00:47:29,015 --> 00:47:31,816
We've been showing it to press this week.

1158
00:47:31,816 --> 00:47:33,297
It works, playing that level 20, 30 times.

1159
00:47:33,297 --> 00:47:35,417
Every single play through, we saw content arise

1160
00:47:35,417 --> 00:47:38,298
that none of us had seen before, mostly minor stuff,

1161
00:47:38,298 --> 00:47:40,899
mostly remarks about something in the environment.

1162
00:47:40,899 --> 00:47:45,761
One Italian journalist had a huge argument with his robot

1163
00:47:45,761 --> 00:47:48,042
and generated a long procedural slanging match

1164
00:47:48,042 --> 00:47:48,982
that none of us had seen.

1165
00:47:48,982 --> 00:47:50,603
We wrote it about two and a half years ago,

1166
00:47:50,603 --> 00:47:52,703
but it surfaced because one person

1167
00:47:52,703 --> 00:47:55,024
was sufficiently horrible to their robot.

1168
00:47:55,024 --> 00:47:55,845
Don't be that guy.

1169
00:47:58,230 --> 00:48:03,153
Equally, today, we had a journalist who was very nice to their robot and had some little

1170
00:48:03,153 --> 00:48:06,955
cuddly-feely conversations with their robot, which I also hadn't seen, because I'm a middle-of-the-road

1171
00:48:06,955 --> 00:48:07,555
kind of player.

1172
00:48:07,555 --> 00:48:10,737
That doesn't happen in 80 days.

1173
00:48:10,737 --> 00:48:14,540
We joke that there is content in 80 days that no one has ever seen, that we haven't seen,

1174
00:48:14,540 --> 00:48:17,962
but it's not really very true, whereas this is somewhat more true.

1175
00:48:17,962 --> 00:48:19,423
It does mean we'll have more typos, though.

1176
00:48:19,423 --> 00:48:24,986
To put that more seriously, it does mean we have a massive problem with stability.

1177
00:48:25,528 --> 00:48:27,109
Stability is now a serious issue.

1178
00:48:27,109 --> 00:48:29,270
We're in the same territory as the Blade Runner game

1179
00:48:29,270 --> 00:48:30,191
and the last Express game.

1180
00:48:30,191 --> 00:48:32,252
And both of those games, the big failure was,

1181
00:48:32,252 --> 00:48:33,873
apart from being both commercial flops,

1182
00:48:33,873 --> 00:48:35,834
which scares the living lights out of me,

1183
00:48:35,834 --> 00:48:40,357
was that all of them went really badly wrong

1184
00:48:40,357 --> 00:48:41,558
if left in the hands of a player

1185
00:48:41,558 --> 00:48:43,579
who didn't understand the system.

1186
00:48:43,579 --> 00:48:47,021
Content chains are fragile, inherently.

1187
00:48:48,025 --> 00:48:52,347
You can get dead ends, where the flow just stops and there's nothing left for anyone to do,

1188
00:48:52,347 --> 00:48:55,608
and Chandler's hero is wandering around the dirty streets of LA going,

1189
00:48:55,608 --> 00:49:00,010
everyone seems okay, I don't have a job, I don't know what to do.

1190
00:49:00,010 --> 00:49:03,871
You can have more subtle things. The system might offer the player far too many options.

1191
00:49:03,871 --> 00:49:08,253
I might be in a dialogue with 20 things I can say, and I don't want 20 things I can say.

1192
00:49:08,253 --> 00:49:13,435
Okay, maybe we handle that on the UI side, but maybe we have a real problem to solve as well.

1193
00:49:13,435 --> 00:49:14,635
Episodes themselves.

1194
00:49:15,275 --> 00:49:19,058
can get stuck in loops, they can repeat themselves, they can otherwise embarrass themselves,

1195
00:49:19,058 --> 00:49:21,360
they can get you stuck in cupboards, whatever.

1196
00:49:21,360 --> 00:49:24,202
All the normal kind of game logic problems are still there,

1197
00:49:24,202 --> 00:49:27,265
but in a nonlinear environment, they're much harder to spot.

1198
00:49:27,265 --> 00:49:30,708
And of course, procedural clues can be total rubbish,

1199
00:49:30,708 --> 00:49:33,390
because procedural generation likes to throw up total rubbish.

1200
00:49:34,720 --> 00:49:36,781
This was one I had just before, while I was writing the talk.

1201
00:49:36,781 --> 00:49:39,342
A chipped antler jug shaped like a rabbit.

1202
00:49:39,342 --> 00:49:41,503
I do know what the rules are that generated this,

1203
00:49:41,503 --> 00:49:43,264
but I have no idea what I was thinking

1204
00:49:43,264 --> 00:49:46,326
when I allowed this thing to be produced.

1205
00:49:46,326 --> 00:49:48,287
I struggle even to picture what this object

1206
00:49:48,287 --> 00:49:50,788
is supposed to be, but there we go.

1207
00:49:50,788 --> 00:49:53,210
I think I literally put in a rule that said,

1208
00:49:53,210 --> 00:49:56,131
if it says shaped like a rabbit, don't say that.

1209
00:49:56,131 --> 00:49:58,313
That's not a thing anyone should ever say.

1210
00:49:58,313 --> 00:49:59,994
What even is a rabbit shape?

1211
00:49:59,994 --> 00:50:00,934
I don't know.

1212
00:50:02,502 --> 00:50:03,662
So what do we do?

1213
00:50:03,662 --> 00:50:05,782
Well, we did this.

1214
00:50:05,782 --> 00:50:08,583
We build a spreadsheet version of the game out of an old

1215
00:50:08,583 --> 00:50:09,143
prototype.

1216
00:50:09,143 --> 00:50:13,304
So this is a big thank you to Yannick Losey, who did the

1217
00:50:13,304 --> 00:50:14,944
JavaScript port of the Ink Engine.

1218
00:50:14,944 --> 00:50:18,045
One of the few benefits that we've seen of open-sourcing

1219
00:50:18,045 --> 00:50:21,706
Ink is this chap built a JavaScript version which

1220
00:50:21,706 --> 00:50:23,026
allows me to do this kind of thing.

1221
00:50:23,026 --> 00:50:24,567
Massive kudos to him.

1222
00:50:25,417 --> 00:50:28,179
This plays the game automatically, right?

1223
00:50:28,179 --> 00:50:30,421
It has the actual ink script,

1224
00:50:30,421 --> 00:50:32,943
and almost all of our game logic is in that ink script,

1225
00:50:32,943 --> 00:50:34,605
precisely to make this easier.

1226
00:50:34,605 --> 00:50:37,747
It bashes through it at random, it runs that script,

1227
00:50:37,747 --> 00:50:39,509
and then when it gets back to the game layer,

1228
00:50:39,509 --> 00:50:40,890
the open world layer,

1229
00:50:40,890 --> 00:50:43,452
it simulates it in that crappy orange box there,

1230
00:50:43,452 --> 00:50:45,033
and those little yellow ones

1231
00:50:45,033 --> 00:50:46,355
are ones that you might have a reason to go to.

1232
00:50:46,355 --> 00:50:47,736
The black square one is one

1233
00:50:47,736 --> 00:50:48,937
that you need more evidence to go to,

1234
00:50:48,937 --> 00:50:50,158
and the gray ones are the ones you can't go to,

1235
00:50:50,158 --> 00:50:52,059
but you have been to, sort of thing.

1236
00:50:52,948 --> 00:50:53,669
So we just run it.

1237
00:50:53,669 --> 00:50:55,770
We just say, right, run this for 10 locations

1238
00:50:55,770 --> 00:50:56,711
and show me the game state.

1239
00:50:56,711 --> 00:50:58,513
Run this for 15 game locations.

1240
00:50:58,513 --> 00:50:58,953
Run this for 25.

1241
00:50:58,953 --> 00:51:01,115
Run this to the end of the game.

1242
00:51:01,115 --> 00:51:02,937
Just run it and see where you get to.

1243
00:51:02,937 --> 00:51:04,438
And most of the times you do that,

1244
00:51:04,438 --> 00:51:05,419
it'll crash at some point.

1245
00:51:05,419 --> 00:51:09,022
It'll say, I'm halfway through the Emperor's Library,

1246
00:51:09,022 --> 00:51:10,543
and I went up the stairs and down the stairs

1247
00:51:10,543 --> 00:51:11,584
and up the stairs and down the stairs,

1248
00:51:11,584 --> 00:51:13,066
and then I dropped the key, and then I went up the stairs,

1249
00:51:13,066 --> 00:51:14,087
and now I can't get down the stairs.

1250
00:51:14,087 --> 00:51:15,488
I've run out of content.

1251
00:51:16,479 --> 00:51:17,380
which is fantastic.

1252
00:51:17,380 --> 00:51:19,881
That would have taken me 16 hours of play,

1253
00:51:19,881 --> 00:51:22,163
generate, if I had generate, or any beta tester.

1254
00:51:22,163 --> 00:51:24,865
So I fix it, recompile, run the simulation again.

1255
00:51:24,865 --> 00:51:27,487
That's not enough, but if I do that all the time,

1256
00:51:27,487 --> 00:51:29,948
every night for a year, I will capture the majority

1257
00:51:29,948 --> 00:51:33,371
of dead ends, loose ends, and essentially runtime errors.

1258
00:51:33,371 --> 00:51:35,872
What we're doing is we're turning the entire game flow,

1259
00:51:35,872 --> 00:51:38,254
an inherently unstable content chain,

1260
00:51:38,254 --> 00:51:39,955
into one large computer program

1261
00:51:39,955 --> 00:51:41,116
we can just set off on its own.

1262
00:51:42,085 --> 00:51:43,347
So that's really good.

1263
00:51:43,347 --> 00:51:47,154
It also spits out the transcript, which you can just read.

1264
00:51:48,160 --> 00:51:50,961
and that's good for redrafting and I can spot typos.

1265
00:51:50,961 --> 00:51:52,102
I just flick through it and go,

1266
00:51:52,102 --> 00:51:54,043
that's not a very good line of dialogue.

1267
00:51:54,043 --> 00:51:55,324
That's not a very good segue.

1268
00:51:55,324 --> 00:51:57,385
I wonder if there's a joke to follow up that line.

1269
00:51:57,385 --> 00:51:58,046
I can go and check.

1270
00:51:58,046 --> 00:52:01,948
And I can see content chains that I don't otherwise see

1271
00:52:01,948 --> 00:52:03,449
because when we play the game,

1272
00:52:03,449 --> 00:52:05,870
we tend to play it a bit the same way every time

1273
00:52:05,870 --> 00:52:08,052
because that's the thing that people do.

1274
00:52:08,052 --> 00:52:10,273
It also spits out all the translations that are generated

1275
00:52:10,273 --> 00:52:12,494
so we can test the translation unlock flow as well

1276
00:52:12,494 --> 00:52:14,435
with the language mechanics.

1277
00:52:16,071 --> 00:52:17,932
So yay, automated testing.

1278
00:52:17,932 --> 00:52:19,493
Everybody's been telling us we should have done this

1279
00:52:19,493 --> 00:52:21,354
for years, but we never got around to it.

1280
00:52:21,354 --> 00:52:22,334
We didn't do it for 80 days.

1281
00:52:22,334 --> 00:52:23,075
I can't think why,

1282
00:52:23,075 --> 00:52:24,736
because it would have solved so many problems,

1283
00:52:24,736 --> 00:52:26,617
but it's actually not that bad.

1284
00:52:26,617 --> 00:52:27,457
It's fine.

1285
00:52:27,457 --> 00:52:29,658
We have this little JavaScript prototype.

1286
00:52:29,658 --> 00:52:30,619
We just run it sometimes.

1287
00:52:30,619 --> 00:52:31,719
It's good for redrafting.

1288
00:52:31,719 --> 00:52:33,320
It's good for checking continuity.

1289
00:52:33,320 --> 00:52:36,902
It's allowed us to push the complexity of the logic we use,

1290
00:52:36,902 --> 00:52:38,683
because I'm more confident that we can test it.

1291
00:52:38,683 --> 00:52:41,104
I'm less terrified that I've done something

1292
00:52:41,104 --> 00:52:42,545
really trivially stupid.

1293
00:52:43,545 --> 00:52:44,306
which is great.

1294
00:52:44,306 --> 00:52:46,546
I can have my robot go off on its own and come back a lot,

1295
00:52:46,546 --> 00:52:49,547
which is the sort of thing that often has edge cases.

1296
00:52:49,547 --> 00:52:51,527
Well, this is great at finding them.

1297
00:52:51,527 --> 00:52:54,768
And it lets us do our game-wide balancing.

1298
00:52:54,768 --> 00:52:56,709
Remember I said that the procedural system

1299
00:52:56,709 --> 00:52:59,009
gave you a single unlock curve?

1300
00:52:59,009 --> 00:53:01,510
Well, this is where I wrote the unlock curve

1301
00:53:01,510 --> 00:53:03,670
in JavaScript running an automated process.

1302
00:53:03,670 --> 00:53:04,970
You tweak it, you tweak it, you tweak it,

1303
00:53:04,970 --> 00:53:05,871
you port it into Unity.

1304
00:53:05,871 --> 00:53:08,471
I've never seen that unlock curve work in Unity

1305
00:53:08,471 --> 00:53:10,972
because we haven't built enough of the game yet,

1306
00:53:10,972 --> 00:53:12,552
but I'm 96% confident it will work.

1307
00:53:13,092 --> 00:53:14,133
because I've already run it.

1308
00:53:14,133 --> 00:53:14,874
That's brilliant.

1309
00:53:14,874 --> 00:53:16,495
That's great.

1310
00:53:16,495 --> 00:53:18,076
Finally, yeah, it catches ink flow bugs.

1311
00:53:18,076 --> 00:53:20,798
And it also helped us improve the ink engine itself

1312
00:53:20,798 --> 00:53:22,979
by capturing some really deep down rare engine

1313
00:53:22,979 --> 00:53:23,980
bugs which were there.

1314
00:53:23,980 --> 00:53:25,161
They're not there anymore.

1315
00:53:25,161 --> 00:53:25,581
Problems?

1316
00:53:28,593 --> 00:53:29,454
I'm coming towards the end.

1317
00:53:29,454 --> 00:53:30,955
Thank you very much for listening.

1318
00:53:30,955 --> 00:53:34,418
It's a bit of a, ah, problems.

1319
00:53:34,418 --> 00:53:37,280
It doesn't understand anything, obviously.

1320
00:53:37,280 --> 00:53:39,862
It has no idea if you've repeatedly called the robot

1321
00:53:39,862 --> 00:53:40,682
by the wrong name.

1322
00:53:40,682 --> 00:53:42,704
It doesn't know if you've walked up and downstairs.

1323
00:53:42,704 --> 00:53:44,525
It doesn't know anything, really.

1324
00:53:44,525 --> 00:53:47,607
You have to read the content to see if it makes any sense.

1325
00:53:47,607 --> 00:53:49,729
It doesn't test anything in the 3D world,

1326
00:53:49,729 --> 00:53:51,910
and there are lots of bugs in 3D worlds.

1327
00:53:51,910 --> 00:53:54,212
Our props disappear behind collision,

1328
00:53:54,212 --> 00:53:55,993
cameras go through bushes, all the usual stuff.

1329
00:53:56,417 --> 00:53:57,978
We are going to have to play this game a lot

1330
00:53:57,978 --> 00:53:59,159
to check all of that,

1331
00:53:59,159 --> 00:54:01,720
but it does at least mean that we are checking that,

1332
00:54:01,720 --> 00:54:04,542
not having to check the story content at the same time.

1333
00:54:04,542 --> 00:54:06,883
It is yet more code to maintain,

1334
00:54:06,883 --> 00:54:08,184
yet more bugs to be introduced,

1335
00:54:08,184 --> 00:54:11,626
yet more disparities between the two layers of the game,

1336
00:54:11,626 --> 00:54:13,627
the JavaScript and the Unity version.

1337
00:54:13,627 --> 00:54:16,369
That's unfortunate.

1338
00:54:16,369 --> 00:54:19,470
And finally, and most importantly,

1339
00:54:19,470 --> 00:54:22,692
randomized play is just the worst simulation

1340
00:54:22,692 --> 00:54:24,593
of human behavior I've ever seen.

1341
00:54:25,820 --> 00:54:27,360
We are better than this.

1342
00:54:27,360 --> 00:54:28,781
We are better than this.

1343
00:54:28,781 --> 00:54:32,282
A random player will go upstairs, downstairs,

1344
00:54:32,282 --> 00:54:33,942
upstairs, downstairs, upstairs, downstairs.

1345
00:54:33,942 --> 00:54:35,562
Okay, I've seen everything and leave.

1346
00:54:35,562 --> 00:54:38,883
And over here is a big shiny object

1347
00:54:38,883 --> 00:54:40,624
with some really interesting plot attached

1348
00:54:40,624 --> 00:54:42,364
and it goes, no, I won't see it.

1349
00:54:42,364 --> 00:54:43,465
And I know as game designers,

1350
00:54:43,465 --> 00:54:45,565
we always give players too much credit

1351
00:54:45,565 --> 00:54:47,326
because actually players walk into an environment,

1352
00:54:47,326 --> 00:54:49,606
completely miss that, completely ignore this,

1353
00:54:49,606 --> 00:54:50,827
focus on one spot on the ground

1354
00:54:50,827 --> 00:54:51,987
and then say, I don't know what to do.

1355
00:54:53,414 --> 00:54:53,834
I know.

1356
00:54:53,834 --> 00:54:58,603
And at least randomised players helps us to break the assumption that people are playing

1357
00:54:58,603 --> 00:55:04,373
your game with any modicum of attention, because they probably aren't, or at least not always,

1358
00:55:04,373 --> 00:55:05,275
even when they mean well.

1359
00:55:06,168 --> 00:55:08,949
But we have had to introduce additional code

1360
00:55:08,949 --> 00:55:11,709
to try and get the random simulation to hit

1361
00:55:11,709 --> 00:55:14,170
any interesting side story content.

1362
00:55:14,170 --> 00:55:17,111
So if there's a particular bit of the narrative,

1363
00:55:17,111 --> 00:55:18,911
which is cool, but it does require you to go

1364
00:55:18,911 --> 00:55:20,912
and talk to this person about this thing,

1365
00:55:20,912 --> 00:55:23,352
we basically have code that says, just do that.

1366
00:55:23,352 --> 00:55:24,413
Just get on and do that.

1367
00:55:24,413 --> 00:55:25,753
Are you near it? Do it.

1368
00:55:25,753 --> 00:55:27,213
No, you're not allowed to leave.

1369
00:55:27,213 --> 00:55:28,114
Do your homework.

1370
00:55:28,114 --> 00:55:29,654
And we need that.

1371
00:55:29,654 --> 00:55:30,874
And that's more code to maintain

1372
00:55:30,874 --> 00:55:32,095
and it's debug specific code,

1373
00:55:32,095 --> 00:55:33,755
so we're not really testing properly.

1374
00:55:33,755 --> 00:55:34,075
I think,

1375
00:55:34,838 --> 00:55:39,060
As we get closer to release, I'm going to let this thing run randomly more often,

1376
00:55:39,060 --> 00:55:40,681
because stability matters.

1377
00:55:40,681 --> 00:55:45,362
But for the moment, we have to kind of hamstring it

1378
00:55:45,362 --> 00:55:47,683
to get it to do the things that we're actually interested in,

1379
00:55:47,683 --> 00:55:48,363
which is a shame.

1380
00:55:48,363 --> 00:55:49,804
I wish there was a smarter way of doing that.

1381
00:55:49,804 --> 00:55:50,084
And that's it.

1382
00:55:55,265 --> 00:55:56,685
That's what we're doing.

1383
00:55:56,685 --> 00:55:59,807
In conclusion, we have a free-form,

1384
00:55:59,807 --> 00:56:03,629
contextually aware interaction across a 3D environment

1385
00:56:03,629 --> 00:56:06,670
entirely made out of authored and specific content

1386
00:56:06,670 --> 00:56:09,312
via easily editable blocks with simply logic,

1387
00:56:09,312 --> 00:56:11,693
with simple logic, with simple additive logic.

1388
00:56:11,693 --> 00:56:14,955
Though the story frame rate is now an issue.

1389
00:56:16,931 --> 00:56:18,492
In general, efficient authoring patterns

1390
00:56:18,492 --> 00:56:20,234
have been utterly critical to us.

1391
00:56:20,234 --> 00:56:22,776
We couldn't do it if we hadn't developed those.

1392
00:56:22,776 --> 00:56:25,498
We still use scale and redundancy

1393
00:56:25,498 --> 00:56:26,539
in the text and dialogue.

1394
00:56:26,539 --> 00:56:29,221
We haven't actually thrown away that crutch at all.

1395
00:56:29,221 --> 00:56:31,042
Automated testing is good.

1396
00:56:31,042 --> 00:56:33,344
Any amount of it appears to be good.

1397
00:56:33,344 --> 00:56:35,726
And our major limiting factor is art cost

1398
00:56:35,726 --> 00:56:36,607
and 3D world markup.

1399
00:56:36,607 --> 00:56:38,608
It's not actually story complexity.

1400
00:56:38,608 --> 00:56:40,730
Our story is doing some nice crazy things

1401
00:56:40,730 --> 00:56:42,331
because I think I can get away with it

1402
00:56:42,331 --> 00:56:44,113
while the art department build another chair.

1403
00:56:45,703 --> 00:56:53,586
So, that's me, and if you'll forgive me, I wanted to finish with one last thought.

1404
00:56:53,586 --> 00:56:58,168
So over the last four years I've done three talks at GDC about interactive narrative and

1405
00:56:58,168 --> 00:57:01,469
the work that we've done at Inkle, which I hope a lot of you have interacted with and

1406
00:57:01,469 --> 00:57:05,831
I hope a lot of you have found at least interesting and perhaps provocative.

1407
00:57:06,838 --> 00:57:09,901
And I think I mentioned earlier that we had a philosophy in the games we make,

1408
00:57:09,901 --> 00:57:11,543
but I think we have something deeper than that.

1409
00:57:11,543 --> 00:57:15,647
I think we have a core principle, which is the thing that makes us do what we're

1410
00:57:15,647 --> 00:57:19,210
doing in the first place, the thing that we strive for and that we want to see in

1411
00:57:19,210 --> 00:57:22,754
narrative games. And I, I saw a good formulation of it. So I thought,

1412
00:57:22,754 --> 00:57:26,177
I thought I'd, I thought I'd share that with you in the last minute of the talk,

1413
00:57:26,177 --> 00:57:27,539
which is this, um,

1414
00:57:29,512 --> 00:57:31,653
The conservation of narrative momentum.

1415
00:57:31,653 --> 00:57:33,514
Obviously that's a massive bastardization

1416
00:57:33,514 --> 00:57:35,155
of what the conservation of momentum is,

1417
00:57:35,155 --> 00:57:36,596
but I've got a math degree, so I don't care.

1418
00:57:36,596 --> 00:57:42,500
And what I think I want to say is that games

1419
00:57:42,500 --> 00:57:45,162
should be striving to conserve narrative momentum

1420
00:57:45,162 --> 00:57:46,083
at all times.

1421
00:57:46,083 --> 00:57:49,325
Every narrative experience, a novel, a film, or whatever,

1422
00:57:49,325 --> 00:57:52,067
has got to feel always like something is happening

1423
00:57:52,067 --> 00:57:55,529
right now, but also something is about to happen just now.

1424
00:57:56,440 --> 00:57:58,661
And both of those things have to be true simultaneously.

1425
00:57:58,661 --> 00:58:01,543
Every writer has to balance resolution and mystery,

1426
00:58:01,543 --> 00:58:05,786
tension and payoff, threat and release all of the time.

1427
00:58:05,786 --> 00:58:07,327
Good narrative games need to do this,

1428
00:58:07,327 --> 00:58:09,209
but it's really hard because the player

1429
00:58:09,209 --> 00:58:10,630
keeps walking into things,

1430
00:58:10,630 --> 00:58:12,431
or repeating the same conversation with an NPC,

1431
00:58:12,431 --> 00:58:16,854
or getting lost, or going in and out of the same door.

1432
00:58:16,854 --> 00:58:20,177
Players are our worst enemy

1433
00:58:20,177 --> 00:58:21,798
when it comes to narrative momentum,

1434
00:58:21,798 --> 00:58:22,899
because they don't even know what it is

1435
00:58:22,899 --> 00:58:24,340
they're supposed to be doing.

1436
00:58:25,735 --> 00:58:28,237
So to conserve narrative momentum as best we can,

1437
00:58:28,237 --> 00:58:30,318
everything that the player does that's awkward,

1438
00:58:30,318 --> 00:58:32,140
we need to gloss over as fast as possible

1439
00:58:32,140 --> 00:58:32,981
and get out of the way.

1440
00:58:32,981 --> 00:58:34,061
I used to write text dimensions,

1441
00:58:34,061 --> 00:58:35,583
parser-based interactive fiction,

1442
00:58:35,583 --> 00:58:37,384
and the single worst thing about those

1443
00:58:37,384 --> 00:58:38,425
is that when you make a typo,

1444
00:58:38,425 --> 00:58:39,906
it says, oh, I don't know that word,

1445
00:58:39,906 --> 00:58:41,888
and then it leaves that on screen.

1446
00:58:41,888 --> 00:58:44,330
It leaves your error in front of you,

1447
00:58:44,330 --> 00:58:45,290
and then if you get two in a row,

1448
00:58:45,290 --> 00:58:46,231
it leaves two errors,

1449
00:58:46,231 --> 00:58:48,313
and if you get three commands wrong in a row,

1450
00:58:48,313 --> 00:58:50,594
you can't see any story anymore,

1451
00:58:50,594 --> 00:58:53,537
apart from all the things you did wrong.

1452
00:58:53,537 --> 00:58:54,057
It's terrible.

1453
00:58:54,938 --> 00:58:56,239
The loss of momentum is appalling.

1454
00:58:56,239 --> 00:58:58,440
Well, okay, these were games designed to be played

1455
00:58:58,440 --> 00:58:59,441
coming out of a printer.

1456
00:58:59,441 --> 00:59:01,942
It's not their fault, but we definitely can do better.

1457
00:59:01,942 --> 00:59:05,844
But a lot of games, those errors are all I see.

1458
00:59:05,844 --> 00:59:07,545
When I'm running around a level and I'm uncharted

1459
00:59:07,545 --> 00:59:08,706
and I've completely got lost

1460
00:59:08,706 --> 00:59:10,107
and I'm being shot from all directions

1461
00:59:10,107 --> 00:59:11,488
and the guys do not stop.

1462
00:59:11,488 --> 00:59:13,529
They come right at me and I have nothing

1463
00:59:13,529 --> 00:59:14,950
but error compounded upon error.

1464
00:59:14,950 --> 00:59:17,612
When I'm trying to play Assassin's Creed in stealth mode

1465
00:59:17,612 --> 00:59:18,952
and the frame rate starts to drop

1466
00:59:18,952 --> 00:59:21,314
because every single NPC in the entire level

1467
00:59:21,314 --> 00:59:22,294
has zoned in on me.

1468
00:59:24,170 --> 00:59:27,791
I'm in a narrative point which is not interesting.

1469
00:59:27,791 --> 00:59:31,133
It's just making me feel like I bottled it.

1470
00:59:31,133 --> 00:59:33,054
The narrative momentum evaporates.

1471
00:59:33,054 --> 00:59:34,034
Okay, maybe the gameplay's fun.

1472
00:59:34,034 --> 00:59:34,294
That's fine.

1473
00:59:34,294 --> 00:59:37,215
But I care about the narrative momentum.

1474
00:59:39,621 --> 00:59:45,762
The player should always be thinking about what they're going to do, not what they're supposed to do.

1475
00:59:45,762 --> 00:59:48,303
Time should always be moving forward.

1476
00:59:48,303 --> 00:59:51,764
Moving forward through the story should be frictionless, which doesn't mean you can't have puzzles,

1477
00:59:51,764 --> 00:59:55,905
but it does mean that attempting to solve a puzzle has got to be part of that narrative.

1478
00:59:55,905 --> 01:00:00,986
For example, if I find a stuck door and I rattle it and it's stuck, that's fine.

1479
01:00:00,986 --> 01:00:04,086
But if I rattle it again, she should say, it's still stuck.

